{"title_page": "League of British Jews", "text_new": "{{More references|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''League of British Jews''' was an [[British Jews|Anglo-Jewish]] [[anti-Zionist]] organization that opposed the [[Balfour Declaration of 1917|Balfour Declaration]] giving British support for the establishment of a Jewish homeland in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]].\n\nThe group was founded in November 1917 by [[Lionel Nathan de Rothschild]],  Sir [[Philip Magnus]] and [[Louis Montagu, 2nd Baron Swaythling]], and was led by Rothschild. It had a small membership, only 18 members in 1917, who were \"recruited from the highly acculturated upper strata of British Jewry.\" Despite its small numbers, the League was highly influential. It folded in 1929. <ref name=\"Kolsky\">{{cite book |last1=Kolsky |first1=Thomas |title=Jews Against Zionism: The American Council for Judaism, 1942-1948 |date=1992 |publisher=Temple University Press |isbn=978-1-56639-009-5 |page=17 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sce5_ldz8mwC&pg=PA17&dq=%22league+of+British+jews%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjRvYyGwO_oAhWYmHIEHb8eB_sQ6AEwAnoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=%22league%20of%20British%20jews%22&f=false |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |last1=Kadish |first1=Sharman |editor1-last=Frankel |editor1-first=Jonathan |editor2-last=Medding |editor2-first=Peter Y. |editor3-last=Mendelsohn |editor3-first=Ezra |title=Studies in Contemporary Jewry: IV: The Jews and the European Crisis, 1914-1921 |date=1988 |publisher=OUP USA/Institute of Contemporary Jewry, Hebrew University of Jerusalem |isbn=978-0-19-505113-1 |pages=96-109 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GmrmCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96&dq=%22League+of+British+Jews%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiQwbOExu_oAhWkknIEHZKaC8UQ6AEwA3oECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=%22League%20of%20British%20Jews%22&f=false |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe League favored settlement in Palestine by British Jews who chose to live there, but opposed the belief that Jews constituted a separate nationality, the position then held by [[Reform Judaism]].<ref name=\"Kolsky\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Letter of 'The Ten' ==\nIn the early twentieth century. immigration from Eastern Europe had greatly expanded the number of British Jews. These new immigrants became the targets of anti-immigrant hostility and allegations of sympathy to [[Bolsheviks|Bolshevism]]. This put the Anglo-Jewish community under considerable pressure.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn April 1919, ten prominent members of the League wrote a letter to the London ''[[The Morning Post|Morning Post]]'' titled \"Bolshevism and Jewry: a Repudiation.\" The letter denounced Bolshevism and criticized articles in unnamed Jewish newspapers that \"can have no other effect than than to encourage the adoption of the theoretic principles of foreign Bolsheviks among foreign Jews who have sought and found a refuge in England.\" The letter endorsed a call by the ''Post'' for British Jews to \"dissociate themselves from a cause which is doing the Jewish people harm all over the world.\" The letter was signed by Rothschild, Magnus, Montagu, [[Marcus Samuel, 1st Viscount Bearsted|Marcus Samuel]], [[Harry Samuel|Harry S. Samuel]], Leonard L. Cohen, [[Israel Gollancz|I. Gollancz]], [[John Monash|John Monash,]] [[Claude Montefiore|Claude G. Montefiore]] and [[Isidore Spielmann|Isidore Spielman]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe letter was highly controversial with the British Jewish community. Though not named, the letter had attacked articles in the Jewish newspapers [[The Jewish Chronicle|''Jewish Chronicle'']] and ''Jewish World'' that had described Bolshevism as a protest against the old social order that had tolerated German militarism. The letter was denounced by the editor of the two newspapers, [[L. J. Greenberg|Leopold J. Greenberg]], who denied Bolshevik sympathies and contended that the letter played into the hands of the [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] press. The [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]] passed a resolution saying that it \"deprecates the letter\" on the grounds that it \"differentiates between British and foreign Jews.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWriting in ''Studies in Contemporary Jewry'' in 1988, [[University of Oxford]] historian [[Sharman Kadish]] asserts that \"League of British Jews simply accepted the thesis, inspired by antisemitism, that Russian Jews were Bolsheviks.\" At the time, he writes, both Bolshevism and Zionism \"were regarded as alien imports and equally capable of undermining the loyalty of newcomers to Britain.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n== League publication ==\nThe views of the League were reflected in a newspaper founded in October 1919, the ''Jewish Guardian,'' edited by Laurie Magnus. Its aim was to provide an alternative to the pro-Zionist ''Jewish Chronicle'' and ''Jewish World.''<ref name=\":0\" />\n<br />\n== See also ==\n*[[American Council for Judaism]]\n*[[Balfour Declaration]]\n*[[Zionism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish anti-Zionism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations established in the 1910s]]\n", "text_old": "{{More references|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''League of British Jews''' was an [[British Jews|Anglo-Jewish]] [[anti-Zionist]] organization that opposed the [[Balfour Declaration of 1917|Balfour Declaration]] giving British support for the establishment of a Jewish homeland in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]].\n\nThe group was founded in November 1917 by [[Lionel Nathan de Rothschild]],  Sir [[Philip Magnus]] and [[Louis Montagu, 2nd Baron Swaythling]], and was led by Rothschild. It had a small membership, only 18 members in 1917, who were \"recruited from the highly acculturated upper strata of British Jewry.\" Despite its small numbers, the League was highly influential. It folded in 1929. <ref name=\"Kolsky\">{{cite book |last1=Kolsky |first1=Thomas |title=Jews Against Zionism: The American Council for Judaism, 1942-1948 |date=1992 |publisher=Temple University Press |isbn=978-1-56639-009-5 |page=17 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sce5_ldz8mwC&pg=PA17&dq=%22league+of+British+jews%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjRvYyGwO_oAhWYmHIEHb8eB_sQ6AEwAnoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=%22league%20of%20British%20jews%22&f=false |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |last1=Frankel |first1=Jonathan |last2=Medding |first2=Peter Y. |last3=Mendelsohn |first3=Ezra |title=Studies in Contemporary Jewry: IV: The Jews and the European Crisis, 1914-1921 |date=1988 |publisher=OUP USA/Institute of Contemporary Jewry, Hebrew University of Jerusalem |isbn=978-0-19-505113-1 |pages=96-109 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GmrmCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96&dq=%22League+of+British+Jews%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiQwbOExu_oAhWkknIEHZKaC8UQ6AEwA3oECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=%22League%20of%20British%20Jews%22&f=false |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe League favored settlement in Palestine by British Jews who chose to live there, but opposed the belief that Jews constituted a separate nationality, the position then held by [[Reform Judaism]].<ref name=\"Kolsky\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Letter of 'The Ten' ==\nIn the early twentieth century. immigration from Eastern Europe had greatly expanded the number of British Jews. These new immigrants became the targets of anti-immigrant hostility and allegations of sympathy to [[Bolsheviks|Bolshevism]]. This put the Anglo-Jewish community under considerable pressure.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn April 1919, ten prominent members of the League wrote a letter to the London ''[[The Morning Post|Morning Post]]'' titled \"Bolshevism and Jewry: a Repudiation.\" The letter denounced Bolshevism and criticized articles in unnamed Jewish newspapers that \"can have no other effect than than to encourage the adoption of the theoretic principles of foreign Bolsheviks among foreign Jews who have sought and found a refuge in England.\" The letter endorsed a call by the ''Post'' for British Jews to \"dissociate themselves from a cause which is doing the Jewish people harm all over the world.\" The letter was signed by Rothschild, Magnus, Montagu, [[Marcus Samuel, 1st Viscount Bearsted|Marcus Samuel]], [[Harry Samuel|Harry S. Samuel]], Leonard L. Cohen, [[Israel Gollancz|I. Gollancz]], [[John Monash|John Monash,]] [[Claude Montefiore|Claude G. Montefiore]] and [[Isidore Spielmann|Isidore Spielman]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe letter was highly controversial with the British Jewish community. Though not named, the letter had attacked articles in the Jewish newspapers [[The Jewish Chronicle|''Jewish Chronicle'']] and ''Jewish World'' that had described Bolshevism as a protest against the old social order that had tolerated German militarism. The letter was denounced by the editor of the two newspapers, [[L. J. Greenberg|Leopold J. Greenberg]], who denied Bolshevik sympathies and contended that the letter played into the hands of the [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] press. The [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]] passed a resolution saying that it \"deprecates the letter\" on the grounds that it \"differentiates between British and foreign Jews.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWriting in ''Studies in Contemporary Jewry'' in 1988, [[University of Oxford]] historian [[Sharman Kadish]] asserts that \"League of British Jews simply accepted the thesis, inspired by antisemitism, that Russian Jews were Bolsheviks.\" At the time, he writes, both Bolshevism and Zionism \"were regarded as alien imports and equally capable of undermining the loyalty of newcomers to Britain.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n== League publication ==\nThe views of the League were reflected in a newspaper founded in October 1919, the ''Jewish Guardian,'' edited by Laurie Magnus. Its aim was to provide an alternative to the pro-Zionist ''Jewish Chronicle'' and ''Jewish World.''<ref name=\":0\" />\n<br />\n== See also ==\n*[[American Council for Judaism]]\n*[[Balfour Declaration]]\n*[[Zionism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish anti-Zionism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations established in the 1910s]]\n", "name_user": "Figureofnine", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/League_of_British_Jews"}
