{"title_page": "36th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)", "text_new": "{{other uses|36th Street (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 36 Street\n| image = 36th Street - Northbound Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Uptown platform\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = white\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| bg_color_2 = #FF6E1A\n| address = 36th Street &amp; Fourth Avenue<br>Brooklyn, NY 11232<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn|Sunset Park]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.65445|N|74.00455|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth center\n| service_header = Fourth center header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B70}}; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small> {{NYC bus link|B35}} (on 39th St)<ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[island platform]]s<br>[[cross-platform interchange]]\n| tracks = 4\n| code = 032\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}\n| wifi = yes\n| accessible = future\n| cross_platform = yes\n| passengers = 4,293,364<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -5.5\n| rank = 109<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | type=express | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | station=Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center | service=Fourth center express}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=local | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | station=25th Street | service=Fourth center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | type=West End | station=Ninth Avenue | line=BMT West End Line | service=West End north}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=local | station=45th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth south local}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=express | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | station=59th Street | service=Fourth south express}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n\n'''36th Street''' is an express [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]], located at 36th Street and Fourth Avenue in [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]. It is served by the [[D (New York City Subway service)|D]], [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] and [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] trains at all times, as well as several [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains during rush hours.<ref>*{{NYCS const|timetable|d}}\n*{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}\n*{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref>\n\nThe 36th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905 and subsequently modified. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 36th Street started on December 10, 1909, and was completed in October 1912. The station opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. \n\n== History ==\n=== Construction ===\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{NYCS color|default}};{{linear-gradient|left|#{{NYCS color|orange}}, #{{NYCS color|yellow}}}}\n|legend =track\n|map=numN315\nuvSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Atlantic Av]]\nudSTR!~dMFADEg\\uvSTR\\udSTR!~dMFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~to [[25th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|25 St]]\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nudSTR\\uv\u00dcSTr\\udSTR\nuv\u00dcSTr\\uv\u00dcSTl\nuv-SHI2r\\uvSTR\\uvSHI2l-\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSHI2gl\\udSHI2+lr\\udSHI2gr\\udSHI2gl\\udSHI2+lr\\udSHI2gr\nudSTR\\udCONTf\\uvSTR\\udCONTf\\udSTR ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Ninth Avenue (BMT West End Line)|9 Av]]\nuedSHI2gl\\uexdSHI2+lr\\uedSHI2gr\\uedSHI2gl\\uexdSHI2+lr\\uedSHI2gr\nuxvSTR\\uvSTR\\uexdSTR\\uedSHI2gl ~~ ~~ ~~ {{BSsplit|Unused 40 St|trackways}}\nuvSHI2l-\\uvSTR\\uv-SHI2r\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nudSTR!~dMFADEf\\uvSTR\\udSTR!~dMFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[45th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|45 St]]\nuvSTR!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59 St]]\n}}\n}}\nThe 36th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":123\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC) on July 1, 1907, and the PSC approved the plan for the line in October and November 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref> The contract for the section of the line that included the 36th Street station, Route 11A4, which extended from 27th Street and 43rd Street, was awarded on May 22, 1908, and approved by the [[New York City Board of Estimate]] on October 29, 1909.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53922207/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway To Be Political Issue|date=December 11, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|page=1|language=en}}</ref> Construction on the segment started on December 10, 1909, and was completed in October 1912.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City and the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT) and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> 36th Street opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening22\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref> As part of the Dual Contracts, the original southern half of the station was closed to make room for an above-ground connection to the BMT West End Line, and a new northern half was constructed.<ref name=\"tracks\" />\n\n=== Renovations ===\nIn July 1959, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) announced that it would install [[fluorescent lighting]] at the 36th Street station and five other stations along Fourth Avenue for between $175,000 and $200,000. Bids on the project were to be advertised on August 7, 1959 and completed by fall 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47783394/bay-ridge-home-reporter/|title=Our Subway Stations To Be Brighter|date=1959-07-10|work=Bay Ridge Home Reporter|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16-17}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 36th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379-380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[Pacific Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Pacific Street]] and 36th Street, on March 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=-HNIAQAAIAAJ&dq=Group+XXX%E2%80%94Broadway-Fourth+Avenue+Line:+pacific+Street,+Union+Street,+9th+Street&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Group+XXX|title=Engineering News-record|date=1969|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref> Funding for the renovation projects came out of the NYCTA's 1969\u20131970 Capital Budget, costing $8,177,890 in total.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c-gxGpL_JNQC&dq=%22Pacific+Street+to+36th+Street+stations%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=10-car|title=Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation|date=1969|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=280, 435, 487|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe station was overhauled from 1996 to 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/36d/36d10.jpg|title=The renovations plaque at 36th Street: Opened 1915, Renovated 1997|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 6, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The changes included rebuilt staircases, retiled walls, new tiling on the floors, upgrading the station's lights, installing [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA]] yellow safety treads along the platform edge, new track-beds for local and express trains and also installing some artwork around the entrance.{{Cn|date=December 2019}} In 2019, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] announced that this station would become ADA-accessible as part of the agency's 2020\u20132024 Capital Program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/mta-headquarters/mta-announces-20-additional-subway-stations-receive-accessibility|title=MTA Announces 20 Additional Subway Stations to Receive Accessibility Improvements Under Proposed 2020-2024 Capital Plan|date=December 19, 2019|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|website=mta.info|access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=500 valign=top|Exit/Entrance\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''M'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Mezzanine\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=500 valign=top|Fare control, station agent\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=6 valign=top|'''P<br>Platform level'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 0px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|<span style=color:#{{NYCS color|default}}>'''Northbound local'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 0px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=500|\u2190 {{rint|newyork|D}} toward [[Norwood\u2013205th Street (IND Concourse Line)|Norwood\u2013205th Street]] (late nights) <small>([[25th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|25th Street]])</small><br>\u2190 {{rint|newyork|N}} late nights, {{rint|nycs|W}} rush hours toward Ditmars Boulevard <small>(25th Street)</small><br>\u2190 {{rint|newyork|R}} toward [[Forest Hills\u201371st Avenue (IND Queens Boulevard Line)|Forest Hills\u201371st Avenue]] ([[Whitehall Street\u2013South Ferry (BMT Broadway Line)|Whitehall Street]] late nights) <small>(25th Street)</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Island platform]], doors will open on the left, right</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|<span style=color:#{{NYCS color|default}}>'''Northbound express'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|\u2190 {{rint|newyork|D}} toward Norwood\u2013205th Street <small>([[Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center]])</small><br>\u2190 {{rint|newyork|N}} toward Astoria\u2013Ditmars Boulevard <small>(Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center)</small>\n|-\n|<span style=color:#{{NYCS color|default}}>'''Southbound express'''</span>\n|<span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|D}} toward [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]] via [[BMT West End Line|West End]] <small>([[Ninth Avenue (BMT West End Line)|Ninth Avenue]])</small> \u2192<br><span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|N}} toward Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue via [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach]]  <small>([[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Island platform]], doors will open on the left, right</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|<span style=color:#{{NYCS color|default}}>'''Southbound local'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|<span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|R}} toward [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge\u201395th Street]] <small>([[45th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|45th Street]])</small> \u2192<br><span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{show by date|2020|04|01\n |4={{rint|newyork|D}} toward Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue late nights <small>(Ninth Avenue)</small> \u2192<br>{{rint|newyork|N}} late nights, {{rint|newyork|W}} rush hours toward [[86th Street station (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street\u2013Gravesend]]\n |5={{rint|newyork|D}} toward Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue via [[BMT West End Line|West End]] late nights <small>(Ninth Avenue)</small> \u2192<br>{{0|\u2192}} {{rint|newyork|N}} toward Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue via [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach]] <small>(45th Street)</small> \u2192<br>{{0|\u2192}} {{rint|newyork|W}} toward [[86th Street station (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street\u2013Gravesend]] rush hours}} <small>(45th Street)</small> \u2192\n|}\n[[File:36th Street BMT Entrance.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Station entrance]]\n36th Street is an express station with four tracks and two [[island platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref> {{NYCS|R}} and {{NYCS|W}} trains provide local service, while {{NYCS|D}} and {{NYCS|N}} trains run express (except during nights when they also run local). South of here, N, R, and W trains continue on Fourth Avenue, while D trains diverge east onto the [[BMT West End Line]]. This is one of two \"36th Street\" stations served by the R train; the other is [[36th Street (IND Queens Boulevard Line)|36th Street]] on the [[IND Queens Boulevard Line]].<ref>{{NYCS const|map}}</ref>\n\nThe station originally featured two mezzanines. The mezzanine in what is now the southern half of the station was originally the northern one. A second southern mezzanine was isolated and closed off when the original southern half of the station was closed to make way for the West End Line. However, it is still intact; it was converted to a signal relay room and can be reached by an intact stairway in the tunnel.<ref>https://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/BMT_4th_Avenue_Line#36th_Street</ref>\n===Exits===\nThe station's only two exits are from the open northern [[mezzanine]] above the tracks at the very south end of the station. Outside [[fare control]], two street stairs lead to the northwest corner of 4th Avenue and 36th Street. Another street stair leads to the northeast corner.<ref name=\"maps\">{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n== Proposed subway under 40th Street ==\nThere are three abandoned trackways south of 36th Street station. One trackway merges with the southbound local track, and the other two trackways are south of the tracks that ramp up to the [[BMT West End Line]]. The triple trackway ramps down to a lower level, under the mainline tracks, and curves slightly east before ending. On the main track level, a [[Bellmouth (railroad terminology)|bellmouth]] going east is visible from a Manhattan-bound local train,<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BPjuw5I22To ''The bellmouth can be seen at 58 seconds (0:58) into this video, just before the 36th Street Station.''</ref> just south of this station. When the subway was planned as part of the Triborough System, use of the South Brooklyn cut was not anticipated, and instead a four-track subway was to be built in 40th Street to reach the equivalent of the Culver and West End lines. The unused junction is to the east side of Fourth Avenue.<ref name=\"tracks\" />\n\n==Nearby points of interest==\n* [[Green-Wood Cemetery]]<ref name=maps/>\n* [[Industry City]]<ref name=maps/>\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|36th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:224|BMT 4th Avenue Line|36th Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150112231643/http://www.stationreporter.net/dtrain.htm D Train]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204051427/http://www.stationreporter.net/ntrain.htm N Train]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150113014240/http://www.stationreporter.net/rtrain.htm R Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/36d/index.php 36th Street Pictures]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606072931/http://mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=D&station=8&xdev=677 36th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.654345,-74.004282&spn=0,359.986567&z=17&lci=transit&layer=c&cbll=40.654442,-74.0044&panoid=n0SciIPLyAbJWBqZ6G4N-g&cbp=12,329.29,,0,8.16 36th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6543642,-74.0042419,3a,75y,76.25h,88.58t/data=!3m8!1e1!3m6!1s-ztbu77CvQa0%2FV6LpQOWkq2I%2FAAAAAAAAO1w%2Fwe2KNVq4vL8Siq7q4fEa64qHvEPH30lbgCLIB!2e4!3e11!6s%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2F-ztbu77CvQa0%2FV6LpQOWkq2I%2FAAAAAAAAO1w%2Fwe2KNVq4vL8Siq7q4fEa64qHvEPH30lbgCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i9728!8i4864!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1!6m1!1e1 Platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|ld=y|ln=y|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:36th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|36th Street (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 36 Street\n| image = 36th Street - Northbound Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Uptown platform\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = white\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| bg_color_2 = #FF6E1A\n| address = 36th Street &amp; Fourth Avenue<br>Brooklyn, NY 11232<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn|Sunset Park]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.65445|N|74.00455|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth center\n| service_header = Fourth center header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B70}}; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small> {{NYC bus link|B35}} (on 39th St)<ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[island platform]]s<br>[[cross-platform interchange]]\n| tracks = 4\n| code = 032\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}\n| wifi = yes\n| accessible = future\n| cross_platform = yes\n| passengers = 4,293,364<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -5.5\n| rank = 109<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | type=express | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | station=Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center | service=Fourth center express}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=local | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | station=25th Street | service=Fourth center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | type=West End | station=Ninth Avenue | line=BMT West End Line | service=West End north}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=local | station=45th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth south local}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=express | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | station=59th Street | service=Fourth south express}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n\n'''36th Street''' is an express [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]], located at 36th Street and Fourth Avenue in [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]. It is served by the [[D (New York City Subway service)|D]], [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] and [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] trains at all times, as well as several [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains during rush hours.<ref>*{{NYCS const|timetable|d}}\n*{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}\n*{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref>\n\nThe 36th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905 and subsequently modified. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 36th Street started on December 10, 1909, and was completed in October 1912. The station opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. \n\n== History ==\n=== Construction ===\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{NYCS color|default}};{{linear-gradient|left|#{{NYCS color|orange}}, #{{NYCS color|yellow}}}}\n|legend =track\n|map=numN315\nuvSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Atlantic Av]]\nudSTR!~dMFADEg\\uvSTR\\udSTR!~dMFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~to [[25th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|25 St]]\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nudSTR\\uv\u00dcSTr\\udSTR\nuv\u00dcSTr\\uv\u00dcSTl\nuv-SHI2r\\uvSTR\\uvSHI2l-\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSHI2gl\\udSHI2+lr\\udSHI2gr\\udSHI2gl\\udSHI2+lr\\udSHI2gr\nudSTR\\udCONTf\\uvSTR\\udCONTf\\udSTR ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Ninth Avenue (BMT West End Line)|9 Av]]\nuedSHI2gl\\uexdSHI2+lr\\uedSHI2gr\\uedSHI2gl\\uexdSHI2+lr\\uedSHI2gr\nuxvSTR\\uvSTR\\uexdSTR\\uedSHI2gl ~~ ~~ ~~ {{BSsplit|Unused 40 St|trackways}}\nuvSHI2l-\\uvSTR\\uv-SHI2r\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nudSTR!~dMFADEf\\uvSTR\\udSTR!~dMFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[45th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|45 St]]\nuvSTR!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59 St]]\n}}\n}}\nThe 36th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line. The plan for the line was initially adopted on June 1, 1905, before being approved by the [[Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of New York]] on June 18, 1906 after the Rapid Transit Commission was unable to get the necessary consents of property owners along the planned route.<ref name=\":123\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC) on July 1, 1907, and the PSC approved the plan for the line in October and November 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref> The contract for the section of the line that included the 36th Street station, Route 11A4, which extended from 27th Street and 43rd Street, was awarded on May 22, 1908, and approved by the [[New York City Board of Estimate]] on October 29, 1909.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53922207/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway To Be Political Issue|date=December 11, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|page=1|language=en}}</ref> Construction on the segment started on December 10, 1909, and was completed in October 1912.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City and the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT) and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> 36th Street opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening22\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref> As part of the Dual Contracts, the original southern half of the station was closed to make room for an above-ground connection to the BMT West End Line, and a new northern half was constructed.<ref name=\"tracks\" />\n\n=== Renovations ===\nIn July 1959, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) announced that it would install [[fluorescent lighting]] at the 36th Street station and five other stations along Fourth Avenue for between $175,000 and $200,000. Bids on the project were to be advertised on August 7, 1959 and completed by fall 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47783394/bay-ridge-home-reporter/|title=Our Subway Stations To Be Brighter|date=1959-07-10|work=Bay Ridge Home Reporter|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16-17}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 36th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379-380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[Pacific Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Pacific Street]] and 36th Street, on March 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=-HNIAQAAIAAJ&dq=Group+XXX%E2%80%94Broadway-Fourth+Avenue+Line:+pacific+Street,+Union+Street,+9th+Street&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Group+XXX|title=Engineering News-record|date=1969|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref> Funding for the renovation projects came out of the NYCTA's 1969\u20131970 Capital Budget, costing $8,177,890 in total.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c-gxGpL_JNQC&dq=%22Pacific+Street+to+36th+Street+stations%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=10-car|title=Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation|date=1969|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=280, 435, 487|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe station was overhauled from 1996 to 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/36d/36d10.jpg|title=The renovations plaque at 36th Street: Opened 1915, Renovated 1997|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 6, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The changes included rebuilt staircases, retiled walls, new tiling on the floors, upgrading the station's lights, installing [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA]] yellow safety treads along the platform edge, new track-beds for local and express trains and also installing some artwork around the entrance.{{Cn|date=December 2019}} In 2019, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] announced that this station would become ADA-accessible as part of the agency's 2020\u20132024 Capital Program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/mta-headquarters/mta-announces-20-additional-subway-stations-receive-accessibility|title=MTA Announces 20 Additional Subway Stations to Receive Accessibility Improvements Under Proposed 2020-2024 Capital Plan|date=December 19, 2019|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|website=mta.info|access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=500 valign=top|Exit/Entrance\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''M'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Mezzanine\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=500 valign=top|Fare control, station agent\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=6 valign=top|'''P<br>Platform level'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 0px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|<span style=color:#{{NYCS color|default}}>'''Northbound local'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 0px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=500|\u2190 {{rint|newyork|D}} toward [[Norwood\u2013205th Street (IND Concourse Line)|Norwood\u2013205th Street]] (late nights) <small>([[25th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|25th Street]])</small><br>\u2190 {{rint|newyork|N}} late nights, {{rint|nycs|W}} rush hours toward Ditmars Boulevard <small>(25th Street)</small><br>\u2190 {{rint|newyork|R}} toward [[Forest Hills\u201371st Avenue (IND Queens Boulevard Line)|Forest Hills\u201371st Avenue]] ([[Whitehall Street\u2013South Ferry (BMT Broadway Line)|Whitehall Street]] late nights) <small>(25th Street)</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Island platform]], doors will open on the left, right</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|<span style=color:#{{NYCS color|default}}>'''Northbound express'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|\u2190 {{rint|newyork|D}} toward Norwood\u2013205th Street <small>([[Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center]])</small><br>\u2190 {{rint|newyork|N}} toward Astoria\u2013Ditmars Boulevard <small>(Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center)</small>\n|-\n|<span style=color:#{{NYCS color|default}}>'''Southbound express'''</span>\n|<span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|D}} toward [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]] via [[BMT West End Line|West End]] <small>([[Ninth Avenue (BMT West End Line)|Ninth Avenue]])</small> \u2192<br><span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|N}} toward Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue via [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach]]  <small>([[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Island platform]], doors will open on the left, right</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|<span style=color:#{{NYCS color|default}}>'''Southbound local'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|<span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|R}} toward [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge\u201395th Street]] <small>([[45th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|45th Street]])</small> \u2192<br><span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{show by date|2020|04|01\n |4={{rint|newyork|D}} toward Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue late nights <small>(Ninth Avenue)</small> \u2192<br>{{rint|newyork|N}} late nights, {{rint|newyork|W}} rush hours toward [[86th Street station (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street\u2013Gravesend]]\n |5={{rint|newyork|D}} toward Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue via [[BMT West End Line|West End]] late nights <small>(Ninth Avenue)</small> \u2192<br>{{0|\u2192}} {{rint|newyork|N}} toward Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue via [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach]] <small>(45th Street)</small> \u2192<br>{{0|\u2192}} {{rint|newyork|W}} toward [[86th Street station (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street\u2013Gravesend]] rush hours}} <small>(45th Street)</small> \u2192\n|}\n[[File:36th Street BMT Entrance.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Station entrance]]\n36th Street is an express station with four tracks and two [[island platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref> {{NYCS|R}} and {{NYCS|W}} trains provide local service, while {{NYCS|D}} and {{NYCS|N}} trains run express (except during nights when they also run local). South of here, N, R, and W trains continue on Fourth Avenue, while D trains diverge east onto the [[BMT West End Line]]. This is one of two \"36th Street\" stations served by the R train; the other is [[36th Street (IND Queens Boulevard Line)|36th Street]] on the [[IND Queens Boulevard Line]].<ref>{{NYCS const|map}}</ref>\n\nThe station originally featured two mezzanines. The mezzanine in what is now the southern half of the station was originally the northern one. A second southern mezzanine was isolated and closed off when the original southern half of the station was closed to make way for the West End Line. However, it is still intact; it was converted to a signal relay room and can be reached by an intact stairway in the tunnel.<ref>https://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/BMT_4th_Avenue_Line#36th_Street</ref>\n===Exits===\nThe station's only two exits are from the open northern [[mezzanine]] above the tracks at the very south end of the station. Outside [[fare control]], two street stairs lead to the northwest corner of 4th Avenue and 36th Street. Another street stair leads to the northeast corner.<ref name=\"maps\">{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n== Proposed subway under 40th Street ==\nThere are three abandoned trackways south of 36th Street station. One trackway merges with the southbound local track, and the other two trackways are south of the tracks that ramp up to the [[BMT West End Line]]. The triple trackway ramps down to a lower level, under the mainline tracks, and curves slightly east before ending. On the main track level, a [[Bellmouth (railroad terminology)|bellmouth]] going east is visible from a Manhattan-bound local train,<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BPjuw5I22To ''The bellmouth can be seen at 58 seconds (0:58) into this video, just before the 36th Street Station.''</ref> just south of this station. When the subway was planned as part of the Triborough System, use of the South Brooklyn cut was not anticipated, and instead a four-track subway was to be built in 40th Street to reach the equivalent of the Culver and West End lines. The unused junction is to the east side of Fourth Avenue.<ref name=\"tracks\" />\n\n==Nearby points of interest==\n* [[Green-Wood Cemetery]]<ref name=maps/>\n* [[Industry City]]<ref name=maps/>\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|36th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:224|BMT 4th Avenue Line|36th Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150112231643/http://www.stationreporter.net/dtrain.htm D Train]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204051427/http://www.stationreporter.net/ntrain.htm N Train]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150113014240/http://www.stationreporter.net/rtrain.htm R Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/36d/index.php 36th Street Pictures]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606072931/http://mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=D&station=8&xdev=677 36th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.654345,-74.004282&spn=0,359.986567&z=17&lci=transit&layer=c&cbll=40.654442,-74.0044&panoid=n0SciIPLyAbJWBqZ6G4N-g&cbp=12,329.29,,0,8.16 36th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6543642,-74.0042419,3a,75y,76.25h,88.58t/data=!3m8!1e1!3m6!1s-ztbu77CvQa0%2FV6LpQOWkq2I%2FAAAAAAAAO1w%2Fwe2KNVq4vL8Siq7q4fEa64qHvEPH30lbgCLIB!2e4!3e11!6s%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2F-ztbu77CvQa0%2FV6LpQOWkq2I%2FAAAAAAAAO1w%2Fwe2KNVq4vL8Siq7q4fEa64qHvEPH30lbgCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i9728!8i4864!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1!6m1!1e1 Platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|ld=y|ln=y|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:36th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "reword", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/36th_Street_station_(BMT_Fourth_Avenue_Line)"}
{"title_page": "Naoto Kidoku", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name=Naoto Kidoku\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|fullname=Naoto Kidoku\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1994|5|12}}\n|birth_place=[[Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi]], [[Japan]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height={{Height|m=1.8}}\n|position=[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n|currentclub=\n|clubnumber= \n|youthyears1=2010\u20132012|youthclubs1=[[Urawa Reds]]\n|years1=2013\u20132016|clubs1=[[Fagiano Okayama]]|caps1=0|goals1=0\n|years2=2017|clubs2=[[SC Sagamihara]]|caps2=0|goals2=0\n|years3=2018\u20132019|clubs3=[[Chachoengsao Hi-Tek F.C.|Chachoengsao Hi-Tek]]|caps3=|goals3=\n|years4=2019|clubs4=[[MOF Customs United F.C.|MOF Customs United]]|caps4=|goals4=\n|nationalyears1=|nationalteam1=|nationalcaps1=|nationalgoals1=\n|manageryears1=|managerclubs1=\n|medaltemplates=\n|club-update=\n|nationalteam-update=\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Naoto Kidoku'''|\u5bc4\u7279 \u76f4\u4eba|Kidoku Naoto|born May 12, 1994}} is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[Association football|football]] player.<ref>{{J.League player|11295}}</ref>.\n\n==Career==\nNaoto Kidoku joined [[J2 League]] club [[Fagiano Okayama]] in 2013. In 2017, he moved to [[J3 League]] club [[SC Sagamihara]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerway}}\n*{{J.League player|11295}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kidoku, Naoto}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football people from Yamanashi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Japanese footballers]]\n[[Category:J2 League players]]\n[[Category:J3 League players]]\n[[Category:Fagiano Okayama players]]\n[[Category:SC Sagamihara players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{Japan-footy-defender-1990s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name=Naoto Kidoku\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|fullname=Naoto Kidoku\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1994|5|12}}\n|birth_place=[[Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi]], [[Japan]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height={{Height|m=1.8}}\n|position=[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n|currentclub=\n|clubnumber= \n|youthyears1=2010\u20132012|youthclubs1=[[Urawa Reds]]\n|years1=2013\u20132016|clubs1=[[Fagiano Okayama]]|caps1=0|goals1=0\n|years2=2017|clubs2=[[SC Sagamihara]]|caps2=0|goals2=0\n|years3=2018\u20132019|clubs3=[[Chachoengsao Hi-Tek F.C.|Chachoengsao Hi-Tek]]|caps3=|goals3=\n|years4=2019|clubs4=[[MOF Customs United F.C.|MOF Customs United]]|caps4=|goals4=\n|nationalyears1=|nationalteam1=|nationalcaps1=|nationalgoals1=\n|manageryears1=|managerclubs1=\n|medaltemplates=\n|club-update=\n|nationalteam-update=\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Naoto Kidoku'''|\u5bc4\u7279 \u76f4\u4eba|Kidoku Naoto|born May 12, 1994}} is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[Association football|football]] player.<ref>{{J.League player|11295}}</ref>.\n\n==Career==\nNaoto Kidoku joined [[J2 League]] club [[Fagiano Okayama]] in 2013. In 2017, he moved to [[J3 League]] club [[SC Sagamihara]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerway}}\n*{{J.League player|11295}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kidoku, Naoto}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football people from Yamanashi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Japanese footballers]]\n[[Category:J2 League players]]\n[[Category:J3 League players]]\n[[Category:Fagiano Okayama players]]\n[[Category:SC Sagamihara players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{Japan-footy-defender-1990s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Japanese footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Japanese association football player\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naoto_Kidoku"}
{"title_page": "Marc Jampole", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Marc Jampole\n| image         =\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     =\t\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1950|7|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = New York City\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = [[Public Relations Executive]] <br> [[Poet]] <br> [[Television news reporter]]\n| nationality = [[United States]]\n| period      =\n| genre       =\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Marc Jampole''' (born July 24, 1950) is an American [[poet]], public relations executive, former television news reporter and political blogger.\n\n==Background and education==\nIn the 1970s, Jampole taught French and German language and literature and filmmaking at the [[University of Washington]].  He also made several avant-garde films that were shown at a number of independent film festivals.<ref name=\"interview\">[http://www.cervenabarvapress.com/MarcJampoleinterview.htm \"Interview with Marc Jampole\", Cervena Barva Press]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJampole formed [http://www.jampole.com/about-jampole-communications/agency-mission/]Jampole Communications, Inc. in 1989.  As principal, Jampole wrote more than 1,800 articles and was a well-known speaker on media-relations and crisis communications. He was frequently quoted in the mass media as a public relations expert.<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Smashing Myths: Many public relations people are headed in the wrong direction.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' November 23, 2004.[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/04328/415961-28.stm]</ref><ref>Sostek, Anya. \"Occupy Movement presents tricky public relations challenge for targeted companies.\"  ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' October 30, 2011. [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/region/occupy-movement-presents-tricky-public-relations-challenge-for-targeted-companies-36309/]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Companies should employ strategies to overcome bankruptcy stigma.\" ''Pittsburgh Business Times.'' December 3, 2001. [http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/stories/2001/12/03/focus4.html]</ref><ref>Lindeman, Teresa. \"Some criticize Target's response to breach as too slow.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' December 20, 2013. [http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2013/12/20/Target-security-breach-affects-up-to-40-million-accounts-Target-victimized-by-major-security-breach/stories/201312200066]</ref>  Jampole also developed communications plans for more than 100 crises and handled three of the largest [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcies in American history - the bankruptcy of [[Alleghany Corporation]] and two [[Penn Traffic Company]] bankruptcies.<ref>Goins, Tony. \"Penn Traffic closing five local Big Bear stores.\" ''Columbus Business First.'' October 10, 2003. [http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2003/10/06/daily36.html]</ref> At the end of 2016, Jampole sold the operations of Jampole Communications to Pittsburgh-based [https://www.wordwritepr.com/]Wordwrite Communications,  where he serves as executive vice president.\u201d<ref>Tascarella, Patty. \u201cLongtime Pittsburgh PR agencies combining.\u201d Pittsburgh Business Times. November 30, 2016</ref>\n\nJampole has written for many publications, including [[Jewish Currents]], [https://www.abi.org/abi-journal]Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abi.org/abi-journal/the-four-stages-of-insolvency-communications-principles-and-a-case-study]|title=The Four Stages of Insolvency Bankruptcy|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2001|website=Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, [[American Book Review]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=American Book Review Volume 36, #4|date=June 2015|work=American Book Review|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Yearning After Love|date=October 2018|work=American Book Review, Volume 39, #6|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Reefer Sanity|date=April 2017|work=American Book Review, Volume 38, #3|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Transitioning to Retirement|date=January 7, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Employers Who Pay for Jury Duty Aid a Pillar of Freedom.|date=January 20, 2015|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Ignore Media at Your Own Risk|date=July 4, 2006|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, [https://www.snpo.org/publications/nonprofitworld.php]NonProfit World, [[IndustryWeek|Industry Week]], [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Banker]American Banker, [https://hospitalnews.com/]Hospital News, Small Business News and many other journals and newspapers. He serves on the editorial board of Jewish Currents and is currently its president. <ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Class Warfare from the Mid-'30s until Today\" ''Jewish Currents.'' February 18, 2014. [http://jewishcurrents.org/class-warfare-mid-30s-today-25019]</ref>\n\n==Poetry==\n\nJampole has published two books of poetry, ''Music From Words'' (Bellday Books 2007) and ''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017).<ref name=\"bellday\">Jampole, Marc.  ''Music from Words'' Bellday Books 2007. [www.belldaybooks.com]</ref> His poems have been published in many poetry journals and anthologies, including ''The Mississippi Review<nowiki>''</nowiki>,<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Dot & Sylvia.\" ''The Mississippi Review'' Vol. 31 #1-2. Spring 2003. {{cite web|url=https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID%3D268 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719010422/https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID=268 |archivedate=2010-07-19 }}</ref> Evansville Review, The Courtland Review,<ref>Jampole, Marc. \u201cInstead of Sex.\u201d ''The Courtland Review'' Issue 46. Feb 2010. [http://www.cortlandreview.com/issue/46/jampole.html?ref=home]</ref> [http://www.vallummag.com/]''Vallum'', [http://www.cutthroatmag.com/]Cutthroat, [[Slant Magazine]], Illumen, [[Oxford Magazine]], [http://www.janushead.org/]Janus Head,<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"These Are a Few,\" \"Divine Amnesia,\" \"A Brother's Funeral.\" ''Janus Head'' #74 \"Addiction 2\". 2004. {{cite web|url=http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830154112/http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-30 }}</ref> Only the Sea Keeps (''2005 Bayeaux Arts Press''),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"If Nature had a Conscious.\" ''Only the Sea Keeps.'' Bayeaux Arts Press. 2005.</ref> [[Wilderness House Literary Review]],<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Garbo at 48.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 2 #4. Winter 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-2.4/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"At the Cocktail Party,\" \"On Manhattan Beach with Love and Thanatos.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 3 #1. Spring 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-3.1/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref> [https://www.ellipsiszine.com/]Ellipsis,<ref>[http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf Jampole, Marc. \"The Wrestler\" ''Ellipsis'' #44.  Spring 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723003242/http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf |date=2012-07-23 }}</ref> Journey (''2009 Eden Waters Press)'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"A Modern Passion.\" ''Journey.'' Eden Waters Press. 2009.[http://edenwaterspress.com/current_issue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314071733/http://www.edenwaterspress.com/current_issue |date=2012-03-14 }}</ref> ''and'' [http://www.acappellazoo.com/]Acapella Zoo,<ref>[http://www.acappellazoo.com/fall08.5 Jampole, Marc. \"The Walk Away.\" ''Acapella Zoo'' #1. Fall 2008]</ref>'' among others.  Four of his poems were nominated for the ''[[Pushcart Prize]],'' one in 1990, and three in ''2008.<ref name=\"bellday\" />''\n\n''Slant: A Journal of Poetry'' references Marc Jampole as a poet whose work verges on the experimental or brash.<ref>[http://uca.edu/english/slant-a-journal-of-poetry/ \"Slant: A Journal of Poetry.\" University of Central Arkansas.]</ref> One critic has noted that \u201cJampole has a wonderful ear for placing words in a way that animates them and gives them active agency\u2026\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=Jeffrey Cyphers|url=|title=Flip Book|date=July-August 2018|work=American Book Review, Volume 39, # 5|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Another has written that \u201cJampole\u2019s poems really sing, remarkably, in a diverse chorus of registers, often with affection and humor.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/poetry-music-imagination/|title=Poetry of Music and Imagination|last=Goldman|first=Janlori|date=Spring 2014|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJampole's work is rarely autobiographical.<ref name=\"interview\" /> The narrators in his poems are sometimes famous people, biblical or historical figures mes ordinary people at a point of epiphany or anagnorisis. In one poem, a real-estate agent who thinks he's [[Moses]] sees the burning bush in an upscale suburb. In others, [[Gilgamesh]] gets caught in a traffic jam, [[Blaise Pascal]] faces a crisis of faith and faith in reason, a former whiz kid disassociates into psychosis and [[Hugo Ball]], one of the founders of the [[Dada]] movement, sells his wife to soldiers.<ref name=\"bellday\" /> He also writes in reaction to world events, such as the 2004 tsunami in Southeast Asia.<ref>Behe, Regis. \"Tsunami project reveals quality of poetry in Pittsburgh area.\" ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review.'' December 25, 2005.[http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_407023.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218085628/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/S_407023.html |date=2010-02-18 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Music from Words'' (Bellday Books 2007)\n*''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017)\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''The Great American Wise Ass Poetry Anthology'' (2016)\n* ''And Love'' (Jacar Press 2012)\n* ''Fusion of Form'' (2009)\n* ''Bagel Bards IV'' (2009) and V (2010)\n* ''Natural Language'' (Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh 2010)\n* ''Journey'' (Eden Waters Press 2009)\n* ''A Poet's Haggadah'' (Ain't Got No Press 2008)\n* ''Along These Rivers'' (Quadrant Publishing 2008)\n* ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (Bayeaux Arts 2005)\n\n===Literary publications===\n*[https://580split.org/]''580 Split''\n*[http://www.acappellazoo.com/]''Acapella Zoo''\n*''ALTE''\n*[http://www.barrowstreet.org/]''Barrow Street''\n*[http://nycbigcitylit.com/]''Big City Lit''\n*[https://blueunicorn.org/]''Blue Unicorn''\n*[https://www.chinagrovepress.com/]''China Grove''\n*''Connecticut River Review''\n* ''[[Cortland Review]]''\n* ''[[Curbside Review''\n*[http://www.cutthroatmag.com/]''Cutthroat''\n*[https://www.ellipsiszine.com/]''Ellipsis''\n*[http://ibbetsonpress.com/]''Ibbetson Street''\n* ''Illumen''\n*[http://www.janushead.org/]''Janus Head''\n* ''[[Jewish Currents]]'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/unionized-public-schools-do-a-better-job/|title=Unionized Public Schools Do a Better Job, But Poverty trumps Teachers Everywhere|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/paul-celan-as-existentialist-poet/|title=Paul Celan as Existentialist Poet|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/is-social-democracy-un-american/|title=Is Social Democracy UnAmerican?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*''Licking Review Review''\n*''Literary Hatchet''\n*[https://mainstreetragbookstore.com/product/the-main-street-rag-winter-2019/]''Main Street Rag''\n*[https://issuu.com/miracleezine/docs/issue8]''Miracle''\n* ''[[Mississippi Review]]''\n* ''Orphic Lute''\n* ''[[Oxford Magazine]]''\n*[http://paperstreetmag.com/]''Paper Street''\n* ''Peralta Press''\n*[https://pittsburghpoetryreview.com/]''Pittsburgh Poetry Review''\n*[https://pittsburghquarterly.com/]''Pittsburgh Quarterly''\n*[http://ratsassreview.net/]''Rat\u2019s Ass Review''\n*[https://www.recoursaupoeme.fr/marc-jampole/]''Recours au Po\u00e9me''\n* ''Rune''\n*[https://sinfronterasjournal.com/]''Sin Fronteras''\n*[https://uca.edu/archives/slant/]''Slant: A Journal of Poetry''\n*[https://www.evansville.edu/majors/creativewriting/evansvilleReview.cfm]''The Evansville Review''\n*[http://www.vallummag.com/]''Vallum''\n*[https://voxpopulisphere.com/]''Vox Populi''\n* ''White Pelican Review''\n*[https://www.whlreview.com/]''Wilderness House Review''\n* ''Yawp!''\n\n===Films===\n*''Tinbad- 1973''\n*''Preludes- 1974''\n*''Judgement of Paris- 1975''\n*''Landscapes of Desire - 2012''\n\n=== OpEdge Blog ===\nJampole has written the [http://www.jampole.com/]OpEdge<sup>TM</sup> blog since 2019. OpEdge discusses the political and social issues of the day from a left-wing point of view, often using academic and secondary research to make the case for his views, including raising taxes on the wealthy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/another-proof-we-need-to-tax-the-wealthy-more-funds-for-investing-in-guitars-stamps/]|title=\u201cAnother proof we need to tax the wealthy more: funds for investing in guitars & stamps.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 25, 2013|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/new-tax-bill-tries-something-thats-already-failed-many-times-lowering-taxes-on-wealthy-to-spur-economic-growth-but-its-typical-of-gop-to-propose-programs-that-have-proven-not-to-wo/|title=New tax bill tries something that\u2019s already failed many times.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 21, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/if-the-goal-is-a-strong-economy-tax-reform-should-lower-taxes-on-poor-raise-them-on-wealthy/|title=\u201cIf the goal is a strong economy, tax reform should lower taxes on the wealthy and rise them on wealthy.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, cutting the military budget<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/u-s-spends-40-of-worlds-total-military-budget-its-controlled-by-an-inconsistent-bellicose-ignoramus-who-favors-disruption-over-working-together-shows-no-regard-for/|title=\u201cU.S. spends 40% of world\u2019s total military budget & it\u2019s controlled by an inconsistent & bellicose ignoramus.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 17, 2018|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/why-is-all-the-talk-about-cutting-payments-to-the-poor-and-elderly-how-about-cutting-defense/|title=\u201cWhy is all the talk about cutting payments to the poor and elderly. How about cutting defense?\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 11, 2012|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and turning away from the celebrity-fueled culture of consumption<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/the-commercialization-of-halloween-has-helped-further-the-infantilization-of-american-culture/|title=\u201cThe commercialization of Haloween has helped further the infantilization of American culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/you-can-ignore-the-royal-wedding-but-not-the-overwhelming-presence-of-celebrity-culture/|title=\u201cYou can ignore the royal wedding, but not he overwhelming presence of celebrity culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 25, 2011|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. National Public Radio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=510628831?storyId=510628831|title=\u201cComic Hero: Why Donald Trump\u2019s Candid Rhetoric Resonates with Supporters.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 19, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and other media have frequently quoted or referenced OpEdge articles. OpEdge articles also often appears on the websites of [https://progressivepopulist.blogspot.com/?m=1]''The Progressive Populist''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://progressivepopulist.blogspot.com/|title=OpEdge|last=|first=|date=|website=The Progressive Populist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'', Jewish Currents''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-making-of-our-tables-one-table/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Making of Our Tables One Table.|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 29, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-truth-vs-republican-whitewashing/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Truth versus Republican Brainwashing.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 16, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-taxes-and-the-politics-of-crass-selfishness/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Taxes and the Politics of Crass Selfishness.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=November 29, 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'',''and Vox Populi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/08/20/marc-jampole-bellicose-nation/|title=Bellicose Nation|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 20, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/10/30/marc-jampole-what-the-murders-teach-us/|title=What the Murders Teach Us|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/12/17/marc-jampole-who-should-the-democrats-nominate-for-president/|title=Who Should the Democrats nominate for President?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 17, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/01/04/marc-jampole-the-left-is-right-to-support-increased-unionization/|title=The Left is Right to Support Increased Unionization|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 4, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/03/27/marc-jampole-a-house-of-cards/|title=A House of Cards|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 27, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/04/03/marc-jampole-the-wages-of-war/|title=The Wages of War|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 3, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/05/01/marc-jampole-a-nation-of-rich-and-poor-with-so-much-going-to-so-few/|title=A nation of rich and poor, with so much going to so few|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=May 1, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/06/07/marc-jampole-weapons-of-math-destruction/|title=Weapons of Math Destruction|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=June 7, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/07/03/marc-jampole-what-exactly-are-capitalism-and-socialism/|title=What exactly are \u201ccapitalism\u201d and \u201csocialism\u201d?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=July 3, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/08/26/marc-jampole-taking-back-the-white-house/|title=Taking Back the White House|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 26, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/08/31/marc-jampole-celebrity-culture-and-the-making-of-donald-trump/|title=Celebrity Culture and the Making of Donald Trump|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 31, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/09/18/marc-jampole-hiding-the-truth/|title=Hiding the truth|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2020/01/08/marc-jampole-murdering-suleimani/|title=Murdering Suleimani|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 8, 2020|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2020/03/13/marc-jampole-weinstein-enters-the-courtroom/|title=Weinstein Enters the Courtroom|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 13, 2020|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jampole, Marc}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Marc Jampole\n| image         =\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     =\t\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1950|7|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = New York City\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = [[Public Relations Executive]] <br> [[Poet]] <br> [[Television news reporter]]\n| nationality = [[United States]]\n| period      =\n| genre       =\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Marc Jampole''' (born July 24, 1950) is an American [[poet]], public relations executive, former television news reporter and political blogger.\n\n==Background and education==\nIn the 1970s, Jampole taught French and German language and literature and filmmaking at the [[University of Washington]].  He also made several avant-garde films that were shown at a number of independent film festivals.<ref name=\"interview\">[http://www.cervenabarvapress.com/MarcJampoleinterview.htm \"Interview with Marc Jampole\", Cervena Barva Press]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJampole formed [http://www.jampole.com/about-jampole-communications/agency-mission/]Jampole Communications, Inc. in 1989.  As principal, Jampole wrote more than 1,800 articles and was a well-known speaker on media-relations and crisis communications. He was frequently quoted in the mass media as a public relations expert.<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Smashing Myths: Many public relations people are headed in the wrong direction.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' November 23, 2004.[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/04328/415961-28.stm]</ref><ref>Sostek, Anya. \"Occupy Movement presents tricky public relations challenge for targeted companies.\"  ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' October 30, 2011. [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/region/occupy-movement-presents-tricky-public-relations-challenge-for-targeted-companies-36309/]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Companies should employ strategies to overcome bankruptcy stigma.\" ''Pittsburgh Business Times.'' December 3, 2001. [http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/stories/2001/12/03/focus4.html]</ref><ref>Lindeman, Teresa. \"Some criticize Target's response to breach as too slow.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' December 20, 2013. [http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2013/12/20/Target-security-breach-affects-up-to-40-million-accounts-Target-victimized-by-major-security-breach/stories/201312200066]</ref>  Jampole also developed communications plans for more than 100 crises and handled three of the largest [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcies in American history - the bankruptcy of [[Alleghany Corporation]] and two [[Penn Traffic Company]] bankruptcies.<ref>Goins, Tony. \"Penn Traffic closing five local Big Bear stores.\" ''Columbus Business First.'' October 10, 2003. [http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2003/10/06/daily36.html]</ref> At the end of 2016, Jampole sold the operations of Jampole Communications to Pittsburgh-based [https://www.wordwritepr.com/]Wordwrite Communications,  where he serves as executive vice president.\u201d<ref>Tascarella, Patty. \u201cLongtime Pittsburgh PR agencies combining.\u201d Pittsburgh Business Times. November 30, 2016</ref>\n\nJampole has written for many publications, including [[Jewish Currents]], [https://www.abi.org/abi-journal]Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abi.org/abi-journal/the-four-stages-of-insolvency-communications-principles-and-a-case-study]|title=The Four Stages of Insolvency Bankruptcy|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2001|website=Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, [[American Book Review]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=American Book Review Volume 36, #4|date=June 2015|work=American Book Review|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Yearning After Love|date=October 2018|work=American Book Review, Volume 39, #6|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Reefer Sanity|date=April 2017|work=American Book Review, Volume 38, #3|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Transitioning to Retirement|date=January 7, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Employers Who Pay for Jury Duty Aid a Pillar of Freedom.|date=January 20, 2015|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jampole|first=Marc|url=|title=Ignore Media at Your Own Risk|date=July 4, 2006|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, [https://www.snpo.org/publications/nonprofitworld.php]NonProfit World, [[IndustryWeek|Industry Week]], [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Banker]American Banker, [https://hospitalnews.com/]Hospital News, Small Business News and many other journals and newspapers. He serves on the editorial board of Jewish Currents and is currently its president. <ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Class Warfare from the Mid-'30s until Today\" ''Jewish Currents.'' February 18, 2014. [http://jewishcurrents.org/class-warfare-mid-30s-today-25019]</ref>\n\n==Poetry==\n\nJampole has published two books of poetry, ''Music From Words'' (Bellday Books 2007) and ''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017).<ref name=\"bellday\">Jampole, Marc.  ''Music from Words'' Bellday Books 2007. [www.belldaybooks.com]</ref> His poems have been published in many poetry journals and anthologies, including ''The Mississippi Review<nowiki>''</nowiki>,<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Dot & Sylvia.\" ''The Mississippi Review'' Vol. 31 #1-2. Spring 2003. {{cite web|url=https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID%3D268 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719010422/https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID=268 |archivedate=2010-07-19 }}</ref> Evansville Review, The Courtland Review,<ref>Jampole, Marc. \u201cInstead of Sex.\u201d ''The Courtland Review'' Issue 46. Feb 2010. [http://www.cortlandreview.com/issue/46/jampole.html?ref=home]</ref> [http://www.vallummag.com/]''Vallum'', [http://www.cutthroatmag.com/]Cutthroat, [[Slant Magazine]], Illumen, [[Oxford Magazine]], [http://www.janushead.org/]Janus Head,<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"These Are a Few,\" \"Divine Amnesia,\" \"A Brother's Funeral.\" ''Janus Head'' #74 \"Addiction 2\". 2004. {{cite web|url=http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830154112/http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-30 }}</ref> Only the Sea Keeps (''2005 Bayeaux Arts Press''),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"If Nature had a Conscious.\" ''Only the Sea Keeps.'' Bayeaux Arts Press. 2005.</ref> [[Wilderness House Literary Review]],<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Garbo at 48.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 2 #4. Winter 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-2.4/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"At the Cocktail Party,\" \"On Manhattan Beach with Love and Thanatos.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 3 #1. Spring 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-3.1/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref> [https://www.ellipsiszine.com/]Ellipsis,<ref>[http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf Jampole, Marc. \"The Wrestler\" ''Ellipsis'' #44.  Spring 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723003242/http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf |date=2012-07-23 }}</ref> Journey (''2009 Eden Waters Press)'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"A Modern Passion.\" ''Journey.'' Eden Waters Press. 2009.[http://edenwaterspress.com/current_issue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314071733/http://www.edenwaterspress.com/current_issue |date=2012-03-14 }}</ref> ''and'' [http://www.acappellazoo.com/]Acapella Zoo,<ref>[http://www.acappellazoo.com/fall08.5 Jampole, Marc. \"The Walk Away.\" ''Acapella Zoo'' #1. Fall 2008]</ref>'' among others.  Four of his poems were nominated for the ''[[Pushcart Prize]],'' one in 1990, and three in ''2008.<ref name=\"bellday\" />''\n\n''Slant: A Journal of Poetry'' references Marc Jampole as a poet whose work verges on the experimental or brash.<ref>[http://uca.edu/english/slant-a-journal-of-poetry/ \"Slant: A Journal of Poetry.\" University of Central Arkansas.]</ref> One critic has noted that \u201cJampole has a wonderful ear for placing words in a way that animates them and gives them active agency\u2026\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=Jeffrey Cyphers|url=|title=Flip Book|date=July-August 2018|work=American Book Review, Volume 39, # 5|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Another has written that \u201cJampole\u2019s poems really sing, remarkably, in a diverse chorus of registers, often with affection and humor.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/poetry-music-imagination/|title=Poetry of Music and Imagination|last=Goldman|first=Janlori|date=Spring 2014|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJampole's work is rarely autobiographical.<ref name=\"interview\" /> The narrators in his poems are sometimes famous people, biblical or historical figures mes ordinary people at a point of epiphany or anagnorisis. In one poem, a real-estate agent who thinks he's [[Moses]] sees the burning bush in an upscale suburb. In others, [[Gilgamesh]] gets caught in a traffic jam, [[Blaise Pascal]] faces a crisis of faith and faith in reason, a former whiz kid disassociates into psychosis and [[Hugo Ball]], one of the founders of the [[Dada]] movement, sells his wife to soldiers.<ref name=\"bellday\" /> He also writes in reaction to world events, such as the 2004 tsunami in Southeast Asia.<ref>Behe, Regis. \"Tsunami project reveals quality of poetry in Pittsburgh area.\" ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review.'' December 25, 2005.[http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_407023.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218085628/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/S_407023.html |date=2010-02-18 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Music from Words'' (Bellday Books 2007)\n*''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017)\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''The Great American Wise Ass Poetry Anthology'' (2016)\n* ''And Love'' (Jacar Press 2012)\n* ''Fusion of Form'' (2009)\n* ''Bagel Bards IV'' (2009) and V (2010)\n* ''Natural Language'' (Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh 2010)\n* ''Journey'' (Eden Waters Press 2009)\n* ''A Poet's Haggadah'' (Ain't Got No Press 2008)\n* ''Along These Rivers'' (Quadrant Publishing 2008)\n* ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (Bayeaux Arts 2005)\n\n===Literary publications===\n*[https://580split.org/]''580 Split''\n*[http://www.acappellazoo.com/]''Acapella Zoo''\n*''ALTE''\n*[http://www.barrowstreet.org/]''Barrow Street''\n*[http://nycbigcitylit.com/]''Big City Lit''\n*[https://blueunicorn.org/]''Blue Unicorn''\n*[https://www.chinagrovepress.com/]''China Grove''\n*''Connecticut River Review''\n* ''[[Cortland Review]]''\n* ''Curbside Review''\n*[http://www.cutthroatmag.com/]''Cutthroat''\n*[https://www.ellipsiszine.com/]''Ellipsis''\n*[http://ibbetsonpress.com/]''Ibbetson Street''\n* ''Illumen''\n* ''Janus Head''\n* ''[[Jewish Currents]]'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/unionized-public-schools-do-a-better-job/|title=Unionized Public Schools Do a Better Job, But Poverty trumps Teachers Everywhere|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/paul-celan-as-existentialist-poet/|title=Paul Celan as Existentialist Poet|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/is-social-democracy-un-american/|title=Is Social Democracy UnAmerican?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*''Licking Review Review''\n*''Literary Hatchet''\n* ''Main Street Rag''\n* ''Miracle''\n* ''[[Mississippi Review]]''\n* ''Orphic Lute''\n* ''[[Oxford Magazine]]''\n* ''Paper Street''\n* ''Peralta Press''\n* ''Pittsburgh Poetry Review''\n* ''Pittsburgh Quarterly''\n* ''Rat\u2019s Ass Review''\n* ''Recours au Po\u00e9me''\n* ''Rune''\n*[https://sinfronterasjournal.com/]''Sin Fronteras''\n*[https://uca.edu/archives/slant/]''Slant: A Journal of Poetry''\n*[https://www.evansville.edu/majors/creativewriting/evansvilleReview.cfm]''The Evansville Review''\n*[http://www.vallummag.com/]''Vallum''\n*[https://voxpopulisphere.com/]''Vox Populi''\n* ''White Pelican Review''\n*[https://www.whlreview.com/]''Wilderness House Review''\n* ''Yawp!''\n\n===Films===\n*''Tinbad- 1973''\n*''Preludes- 1974''\n*''Judgement of Paris- 1975''\n*''Landscapes of Desire - 2012''\n\n=== OpEdge Blog ===\nJampole has written the [http://www.jampole.com/]OpEdge<sup>TM</sup> blog since 2019. OpEdge discusses the political and social issues of the day from a left-wing point of view, often using academic and secondary research to make the case for his views, including raising taxes on the wealthy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/another-proof-we-need-to-tax-the-wealthy-more-funds-for-investing-in-guitars-stamps/]|title=\u201cAnother proof we need to tax the wealthy more: funds for investing in guitars & stamps.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 25, 2013|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/new-tax-bill-tries-something-thats-already-failed-many-times-lowering-taxes-on-wealthy-to-spur-economic-growth-but-its-typical-of-gop-to-propose-programs-that-have-proven-not-to-wo/|title=New tax bill tries something that\u2019s already failed many times.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 21, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/if-the-goal-is-a-strong-economy-tax-reform-should-lower-taxes-on-poor-raise-them-on-wealthy/|title=\u201cIf the goal is a strong economy, tax reform should lower taxes on the wealthy and rise them on wealthy.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, cutting the military budget<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/u-s-spends-40-of-worlds-total-military-budget-its-controlled-by-an-inconsistent-bellicose-ignoramus-who-favors-disruption-over-working-together-shows-no-regard-for/|title=\u201cU.S. spends 40% of world\u2019s total military budget & it\u2019s controlled by an inconsistent & bellicose ignoramus.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 17, 2018|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/why-is-all-the-talk-about-cutting-payments-to-the-poor-and-elderly-how-about-cutting-defense/|title=\u201cWhy is all the talk about cutting payments to the poor and elderly. How about cutting defense?\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 11, 2012|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and turning away from the celebrity-fueled culture of consumption<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/the-commercialization-of-halloween-has-helped-further-the-infantilization-of-american-culture/|title=\u201cThe commercialization of Haloween has helped further the infantilization of American culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/you-can-ignore-the-royal-wedding-but-not-the-overwhelming-presence-of-celebrity-culture/|title=\u201cYou can ignore the royal wedding, but not he overwhelming presence of celebrity culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 25, 2011|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. National Public Radio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=510628831?storyId=510628831|title=\u201cComic Hero: Why Donald Trump\u2019s Candid Rhetoric Resonates with Supporters.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 19, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and other media have frequently quoted or referenced OpEdge articles. OpEdge articles also often appears on the websites of [https://progressivepopulist.blogspot.com/?m=1]''The Progressive Populist''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://progressivepopulist.blogspot.com/|title=OpEdge|last=|first=|date=|website=The Progressive Populist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'', Jewish Currents''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-making-of-our-tables-one-table/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Making of Our Tables One Table.|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 29, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-truth-vs-republican-whitewashing/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Truth versus Republican Brainwashing.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 16, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-taxes-and-the-politics-of-crass-selfishness/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Taxes and the Politics of Crass Selfishness.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=November 29, 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'',''and Vox Populi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/08/20/marc-jampole-bellicose-nation/|title=Bellicose Nation|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 20, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/10/30/marc-jampole-what-the-murders-teach-us/|title=What the Murders Teach Us|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2018/12/17/marc-jampole-who-should-the-democrats-nominate-for-president/|title=Who Should the Democrats nominate for President?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 17, 2018|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/01/04/marc-jampole-the-left-is-right-to-support-increased-unionization/|title=The Left is Right to Support Increased Unionization|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 4, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/03/27/marc-jampole-a-house-of-cards/|title=A House of Cards|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 27, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/04/03/marc-jampole-the-wages-of-war/|title=The Wages of War|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 3, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/05/01/marc-jampole-a-nation-of-rich-and-poor-with-so-much-going-to-so-few/|title=A nation of rich and poor, with so much going to so few|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=May 1, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/06/07/marc-jampole-weapons-of-math-destruction/|title=Weapons of Math Destruction|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=June 7, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/07/03/marc-jampole-what-exactly-are-capitalism-and-socialism/|title=What exactly are \u201ccapitalism\u201d and \u201csocialism\u201d?|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=July 3, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/08/26/marc-jampole-taking-back-the-white-house/|title=Taking Back the White House|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 26, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/08/31/marc-jampole-celebrity-culture-and-the-making-of-donald-trump/|title=Celebrity Culture and the Making of Donald Trump|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 31, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2019/09/18/marc-jampole-hiding-the-truth/|title=Hiding the truth|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2019|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2020/01/08/marc-jampole-murdering-suleimani/|title=Murdering Suleimani|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 8, 2020|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxpopulisphere.com/2020/03/13/marc-jampole-weinstein-enters-the-courtroom/|title=Weinstein Enters the Courtroom|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 13, 2020|website=Vox Populi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jampole, Marc}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Aristein", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLiterary publications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marc_Jampole"}
{"title_page": "Maronite Catholic Eparchy of Saint Charbel in Buenos Aires", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Eparchy<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = San Charbel in Buenos Aires (Maronite)\n| latin             = Eparchia Sancti Sarbelii Bona\u00ebrensis Maronitarum\n| local             = Eparqu\u00eda de San Charbel en Buenos Aires\n| image             = \n| image_size        = frameless \n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[Argentina]]\n| metropolitan      = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]]\n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = <!-- Area in square kilometers, automatically converted --> \n| population        = \n| population_as_of  = 2010\n| catholics         = 750,000<ref>[http://www.maronite-heritage.com/LNE.php?page=Statistics maronite-heritage.com]</ref><!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = \n| parishes          = 4\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| sui_iuris_church  = [[Maronite Church]]\n| rite              = [[Antiochene rite#Syriac liturgies|West Syro-Antiochene Rite]]\n| established       = 5 October 1990 ({{age|1990|10|5}} years ago)\n| cathedral         = Saint Maron in [[Buenos Aires]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[Charbel Makhluf|St Charbel Makhluf]]\n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}}\n| patriarch         = [[Bechara Boutros al-Rahi]]\n| bishop_title      = Eparch\n| bishop            = [[Habib Chamieh]]\n| metro_archbishop  = [[Mario Aurelio Poli]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| apostolic_admin   = \n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Charbel Georges Merhi]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = \n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.misionlibanesa.com.ar/ Website of the Eparchy] \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Maronite Catholic Eparchy of San Charbel in Buenos Aires'''<ref>[http://www.aicaold.com.ar//index2.php?pag=diomaronita aicaold.com.ar]</ref> (Spanish: '''Eparqu\u00eda de San Charbel en Buenos Aires'''; Latin: '''Eparchia Sancti Sarbelii Bona\u00ebrensis Maronitarum''') is an [[eparchy]] ([[Eastern Catholic]] [[diocese]]) in the [[Maronite Catholic Church]] ''sui iuris'' ([[Antiochian Rite]]) covering [[Argentina]] ([[South America]]).\n\nIt has a [[cathedral]] episcopal see, the Catedral San Mar\u00f3n, located in the national capital [[Buenos Aires]]. In 2010 there were 750,000 members.<ref>[http://www.maronite-heritage.com/LNE.php?page=Statistics maronite-heritage.com]</ref> It is governed by [[Habib Chamieh]], [[Mariamite Maronite Order]].\n\n== History ==\nFrom July 5, 1901 began to come to Argentina the first [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Lebanese Maronite]] missionaries who founded the first mission in the [[Lebanese diaspora]] in South America.\n\nThe Eparchy of San Charbel was established by [[Pope John Paul II]] on 5 October 1990, on territory previously without proper ordinary of the particular church. It is named after its [[patron saint]], [[Charbel Makhluf]].\n\n== Territory and statistics ==\nThe jurisdiction of the eparchy extends to all Maronite Catholic faithful living in Argentina. Its eparchial seat is the Argentine capital, [[Buenos Aires]], where is located the Saint Maron Cathedral.<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/churches/southamerica/3385.htm gcatholic.org]</ref>\n\nIt is not exempt, nor a hierarchical part of the Maronite patriarchal ecclesiastical structure, but a [[suffragan]] see in the [[Ecclesiastical province]] of the Roman Rite Metropolitan [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Buenos Aires|Archdiocese of Buenos Aires]] in Argentina, like its Ukrainian Catholic counterpart, the Eparchy [[Santa Mar\u00eda del Patrocinio en Buenos Aires]].\n\nThe Christians of this diocese are mostly [[Lebanese Argentines|emigrants]] and are originally from [[Lebanon]]. Their naming is originated from Saint [[Maron]] the founder of the Maronite Church. The Eparchy of Saint Charbel of Buenos Aires counted some 750,000<ref>[http://www.maronite-heritage.com/LNE.php?page=Statistics maronite-heritage.com]</ref> Lebanese Maronite Catholics of prevalent [[Arab Christians|Arab Christian]] origin in 2010 and there were four parishes.\n\n==Episcopal ordinaries==\n;Eparchs of San Charbel of Buenos Aires\n* [[Charbel Georges Merhi]], [[Congregation of the Lebanese Maronite Missionaries]] (M.L.M.) (5 October 1990 \u2013 17 April 2013)\n*[[Habib Chamieh]], [[Mariamite Maronite Order]] (O.M.M., Aleppians) (22 November 2019<ref>{{cite press release | access-date = 22 November 2019 | date= 22 November 2019 | publisher = Holy See Press Office | title = Rinunce e nomine, 22.11.2019 | language = it | url = https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2019/11/22/0912/01905.html}}</ref> \u2013 present)\n** Apostolic Administrator from 17 April 2013 to 22 November 2019\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Catholicism|Lebanon|Argentina}}}}\n\n*[[Christianity in Lebanon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Additional sources \n* Ecclesiastical Guide of Argentina (AICA), Catholic Argentina Agency.\n\n==Sources and external links==\n* [http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/zcha0.htm GigaCatholic]\n* [http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dbama.html Catholic Hierarchy]\n\n{{coord missing|Argentina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:San Charbel of Buenos Aires, Maronite Catholic Eparchy}}\n[[Category:Lebanese Argentine]]\n[[Category:Eastern Catholicism in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Maronite Catholic eparchies]]\n[[Category:Maronite Church in South America]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Religion in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1990]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-RC-diocese-stub}}\n{{EasternCatholic-diocese-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Eparchy<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = San Charbel in Buenos Aires (Maronite)\n| latin             = Eparchia Sancti Sarbelii Bona\u00ebrensis Maronitarum\n| local             = Eparqu\u00eda de San Charbel en Buenos Aires\n| image             = \n| image_size        = frameless \n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[Argentina]]\n| metropolitan      = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]]\n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = <!-- Area in square kilometers, automatically converted --> \n| population        = \n| population_as_of  = 2010\n| catholics         = 750,000<ref>[http://www.maronite-heritage.com/LNE.php?page=Statistics maronite-heritage.com]</ref><!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = \n| parishes          = 4\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| sui_iuris_church  = [[Maronite Church]]\n| rite              = [[Antiochene rite#Syriac liturgies|West Syro-Antiochene Rite]]\n| established       = 5 October 1990 ({{age|1990|10|5}} years ago)\n| cathedral         = Saint Maron in [[Buenos Aires]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[Charbel Makhluf|St Charbel Makhluf]]\n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}}\n| patriarch         = [[Bechara Boutros al-Rahi]]\n| bishop_title      = Eparch\n| bishop            = [[Habib Chamieh]]\n| metro_archbishop  = [[Mario Aurelio Poli]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| apostolic_admin   = \n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Charbel Georges Merhi]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = \n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.misionlibanesa.com.ar/ Website of the Eparchy] \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Maronite Catholic Eparchy of San Charbel in Buenos Aires'''<ref>[http://www.aicaold.com.ar//index2.php?pag=diomaronita aicaold.com.ar]</ref> (Spanish: '''Eparqu\u00eda de San Charbel en Buenos Aires'''; Latin: '''Eparchia Sancti Sarbelii Bona\u00ebrensis Maronitarum''') is an [[eparchy]] ([[Eastern Catholic]] [[diocese]]) in the [[Maronite Catholic Church]] ''sui iuris'' ([[Antiochian Rite]]) covering [[Argentina]] ([[South America]]).\n\nIt has a [[cathedral]] episcopal see, the Catedral San Mar\u00f3n, located in the national capital [[Buenos Aires]]. In 2010 there were 750,000 members.<ref>[http://www.maronite-heritage.com/LNE.php?page=Statistics maronite-heritage.com]</ref> It is governed by [[Habib Chamieh]], [[Mariamite Maronite Order]].\n\n== History ==\nFrom July 5, 1901 began to come to Argentina the first [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Lebanese Maronite]] missionaries who founded the first mission in the [[Lebanese diaspora]] in South America.\n\nThe Eparchy of San Charbel was established by [[Pope John Paul II]] on 5 October 1990, on territory previously without proper ordinary of the particular church. It is named after its [[patron saint]], [[Charbel Makhluf]].\n\n== Territory and statistics ==\nThe jurisdiction of the eparchy extends to all Maronite Catholic faithful living in Argentina. Its eparchial seat is the Argentine capital, [[Buenos Aires]], where is located the Saint Maron Cathedral.<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/churches/southamerica/3385.htm gcatholic.org]</ref>\n\nIt is not exempt, nor a hierarchical part of the Maronite patriarchal ecclesiastical structure, but a [[suffragan]] see in the [[Ecclesiastical province]] of the Roman Rite Metropolitan [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Buenos Aires|Archdiocese of Buenos Aires]] in Argentina, like its Ukrainian Catholic counterpart, the Eparchy [[Santa Mar\u00eda del Patrocinio en Buenos Aires]].\n\nThe Christians of this diocese are mostly [[Lebanese Argentines|emigrants]] and are originally from [[Lebanon]]. Their naming is originated from Saint [[Maron]] the founder of the Maronite Church. The Eparchy of Saint Charbel of Buenos Aires counted some 750,000<ref>[http://www.maronite-heritage.com/LNE.php?page=Statistics maronite-heritage.com]</ref> Lebanese Maronite Catholics of prevailent [[Arab Christians|Arab Christian]] origin in 2010 and there were four parishes.\n\n==Episcopal ordinaries==\n;Eparchs of San Charbel of Buenos Aires\n* [[Charbel Georges Merhi]], [[Congregation of the Lebanese Maronite Missionaries]] (M.L.M.) (5 October 1990 \u2013 17 April 2013)\n*[[Habib Chamieh]], [[Mariamite Maronite Order]] (O.M.M., Aleppians) (22 November 2019<ref>{{cite press release | access-date = 22 November 2019 | date= 22 November 2019 | publisher = Holy See Press Office | title = Rinunce e nomine, 22.11.2019 | language = it | url = https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2019/11/22/0912/01905.html}}</ref> \u2013 present)\n** Apostolic Administrator from 17 April 2013 to 22 November 2019\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Catholicism|Lebanon|Argentina}}}}\n\n*[[Christianity in Lebanon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Additional sources \n* Ecclesiastical Guide of Argentina (AICA), Catholic Argentina Agency.\n\n==Sources and external links==\n* [http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/zcha0.htm GigaCatholic]\n* [http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dbama.html Catholic Hierarchy]\n\n{{coord missing|Argentina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:San Charbel of Buenos Aires, Maronite Catholic Eparchy}}\n[[Category:Lebanese Argentine]]\n[[Category:Eastern Catholicism in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Maronite Catholic eparchies]]\n[[Category:Maronite Church in South America]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Religion in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1990]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-RC-diocese-stub}}\n{{EasternCatholic-diocese-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maronite_Catholic_Eparchy_of_Saint_Charbel_in_Buenos_Aires"}
{"title_page": "Nurmij\u00e4rvi", "text_new": "{{for|the former lake|Nurmij\u00e4rvi (lake)}}\n{{Infobox Finnish Municipality\n|name                   = Nurmij\u00e4rvi\n|official_name          = {{lang|fi|Nurmij\u00e4rven kunta}}<br />{{lang|sv|Nurmij\u00e4rvi kommun}}\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \n|native_name_lang       = \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Municipality\n|total_type             = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = Nurmij\u00e4rven kirkko.jpg\n|image_caption          = [[Nurmij\u00e4rvi church]]\n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              = \n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              = \n|image_shield           = Nurmijarvi.vaakuna.svg\n|shield_size            = \n|image_blank_emblem     = \n|blank_emblem_type      = \n|blank_emblem_size      = \n|image_map              = Nurmij\u00e4rvi.sijainti.suomi.2008.svg\n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = Location of Nurmij\u00e4rvi in [[Finland]]\n|image_dot_map          = \n|dot_mapsize            = \n|dot_map_caption        = \n|dot_x =  |dot_y = \n|pushpin_map            = <!-- name of a location map as per Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|province               = [[Southern Finland]]\n|region                 = [[Uusimaa]]\n|subregion              = Helsinki sub-region\n<!-- Smaller parts (e.g. boroughs of a city) and seat of government -->\n|seat_type              = \n|seat                   = \n|parts_type             = \n|parts_style            = <!-- =list (for list), coll (for collapsed list), para (for paragraph format)\n                               Default is list if up to 5 items, coll if more than 5-->\n|parts                  = <!-- parts text, or header for parts list -->\n|p1                     = \n|p2                     = <!-- etc. up to p10: for separate parts to be listed-->\n|government_footnotes   = \n|leader_title           = Municipal manager\n|leader_name            = Outi M\u00e4kel\u00e4\n|leader_title1          = \n|leader_name1           = \n|leader_title2          = \n|leader_name2           = \n|leader_title3          = \n|leader_name3           = \n|established_title      = [[Charter]]\n|established_date       = 1605\n|established_title2     = \n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     = \n|established_date3      = \n|extinct_title          = \n|extinct_date           = \n|area_urban_km2         = \n|area_metro_km2         = \n|population_metro       = \n|population_blank1_title  = \n|population_blank1        = \n|population_density_metro_km2 = \n|population_urban       = \n|population_density_urban_km2 = \n|population_note        = \n|finnish_official       = \n|swedish_official       = \n|sami_official          = \n|urbanisation           = \n|unemployment           = \n|blank1_name            = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank1_info            = [[Humid continental climate#Mild/cool summer subtype|Dfb]]\n|blank2_name            = \n|blank2_info            = \n|blank3_name            = \n|blank3_info            = \n|blank4_name            = \n|blank4_info            = \n|coordinates_type       = \n<!-- latNS=N and longEW=E set by default -->\n|coordinates            = {{coord|60|28|N|024|48.5|E|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = \n|postal_code            = \n|website                = [http://www.nurmijarvi.fi/ www.nurmijarvi.fi]\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Nurmij\u00e4rvi''' ({{IPA-fi|\u02c8nurmi\u02ccj\u00e6r\u028bi}}) is the most populated [[rural]] [[municipalities of Finland|municipality]] of [[Finland]], located {{convert|37|km}} north of the [[Capital (political)|capital]] [[Helsinki]]. The neighboring municipalities of Nurmij\u00e4rvi are [[Espoo]], [[Vantaa]], [[Tuusula]], [[Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4]] and [[Vihti]], and it is part of the [[Greater Helsinki]]. The population of the municipality is {{formatnum: {{Data Finland municipality/population count|Nurmij\u00e4rvi}} }} inhabitants.<ref>[http://pxnet2.stat.fi/PXWeb/pxweb/fi/StatFin/StatFin__vrm__vamuu/statfin_vamuu_pxt_11lj.px/table/tableViewLayout1/ 11lj -- V\u00e4est\u00f6rakenteen ennakkotiedot alueittain, 2019M01*-2019M11*] (in Finnish)</ref>\n\nThe close proximity to Helsinki has led to a considerable growth of the major villages such as [[Klaukkala]], [[Rajam\u00e4ki]] and [[R\u00f6ykk\u00e4]]. Klaukkala is the biggest built-up area of Nurmij\u00e4rvi, which nowadays is considered a dormitory town of Helsinki. The church village (''Kirkonkyl\u00e4'') is the [[administrative centre]] of the municipality.\n\nNurmij\u00e4rvi literally means \"lawn lake\" although the [[Nurmij\u00e4rvi (lake)|lake that gave the municipality its name]] was drained in the early 20th century and is now nothing more than some flat fields near the village centre. Nurmij\u00e4rvi is one of three municipalities in the [[Uusimaa]] region that do not have a Swedish name; the others are [[Askola]] and [[M\u00e4nts\u00e4l\u00e4]].\n\nNurmij\u00e4rvi is best known as the birthplace of Finland's national author, [[Aleksis Kivi]]. The coat of arms of municipality refers to his most famous literal work, ''[[Seitsem\u00e4n veljest\u00e4]]'' (literally translated \"the seven brothers\") from 1870. On January 29, 2020, Nurmij\u00e4rvi declared itself officially the Capital of Aleksis Kivi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nurmijarvenuutiset.fi/artikkeli/837130-nurmijarvi-on-nyt-virallisesti-aleksis-kivi-paakaupunki|title=Nurmij\u00e4rvi on nyt virallisesti Aleksis Kivi p\u00e4\u00e4kaupunki|first=Riikka|last=Laine|publisher=Nurmij\u00e4rven Uutiset|date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020|language=fi}}</ref>\n\n[[Matti Vanhanen]], former [[Prime Minister of Finland]], lives in [[Leps\u00e4m\u00e4]] in Nurmij\u00e4rvi.\n\n== Geography ==\nNurmij\u00e4rvi is located in the central part of Uusimaa. [[Salpausselk\u00e4]] passes through the northern part of the municipality via R\u00f6ykk\u00e4, Kiljava and Rajam\u00e4ki, and the [[Vantaa (river)|River Vantaa]] flows through the Nukari and Palojoki rivers in the eastern part of the municipality. Nurmij\u00e4rvi's lowest terrain is in the Luhtajoki valley at Klaukkala and the highest in Salpausselk\u00e4 near Herunen.\n\nThere are few watercourses in the Nurmij\u00e4rvi area. The municipality is located along the middle course of the River Vantaa and there are two large [[rapids]], the Nukarinkoski and the Myllykoski. The River Vantaa is joined by the Palojoki River from Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4 and Tuusula, near the Palojoki village. The Leps\u00e4m\u00e4 River and the [[Luhtajoki|Luhtajoki River]] flowing in the southern part of the municipality join the Vantaa town side near the [[Keimola]] village before joining the River Vantaa. The largest lake in Nurmij\u00e4rvi is the Lake S\u00e4\u00e4ksi, which is partly situated on the northwest side of Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4, and the other lakes are Lake Vaaksi near R\u00f6ykk\u00e4 and Lake Valkj\u00e4rvi between Klaukkala and Perttula.\n\n=== Villages ===\n[[File:Centre_nurmij\u00e4rvi.jpg|thumb|Aleksis Kiven tie, one of the main streets of Nurmij\u00e4rvi's centre in January 2020.]]\n[[Herunen]], [[J\u00e4rventausta]], [[Kiljava]], [[Klaukkala]], [[Lepp\u00e4lampi]], [[Leps\u00e4m\u00e4]], [[Luhtajoki, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Luhtajoki]], [[Mets\u00e4kyl\u00e4, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Mets\u00e4kyl\u00e4]], [[Nukari]], [[Numlahti]], [[Nummenp\u00e4\u00e4]], [[Nurmij\u00e4rvi (village)|Nurmij\u00e4rvi]] (''Kirkonkyl\u00e4''), [[Palojoki]], [[Perttula]], [[Raala]], [[Rajam\u00e4ki]], [[R\u00f6ykk\u00e4]], [[Suomies]], [[Uotila, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Uotila]], [[Valkj\u00e4rvi, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Valkj\u00e4rvi]]\n\n== History ==\nThe area of what is now Nurmij\u00e4rvi was inhabited in prehistoric times, which refers to archaeological finds dating back to [[5th millennium BC|4500]]-[[4th millennium BC|3500 BC]]. At the time of the [[Middle Age]]s there was no permanent settlement in the area, but later the settlement spread from both [[Tavastia (historical province)|Tavastia]] and the coast to 15 villages in 1540 with 115 houses.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nurmijarvi.fi/kuntalaisen-palvelut/kulttuuri-ja-vapaa-aika/museo/nurmijarven-historiaa/nurmijarven-historiaa-lyhyesti/|title=Nurmij\u00e4rven historiaa lyhyesti|website=Nurmijarvi.fi|accessdate=February 22, 2020|language=fi}}</ref>\n\nAdministratively, Lake Nurmij\u00e4rvi has been formed by combining the districts of [[Loppi]], [[Vihti]] and [[Vantaa|Helsinki parish]]. The earliest documentary mention of Nurmij\u00e4rvi dates back to 1488, when the village of [[Uotila, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Uotila]] was mentioned. According to the land register of 1539, Nurmij\u00e4rvi had 15 villages with a total of 113 houses. An independent congregation had already been formed in 1605 and the administrator of Nurmij\u00e4rvi was born in 1775, when the area had a population of 1471.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nThe first church in Lake Nurmij\u00e4rvi, which must have been St. Martin's Church in 1565, was built at the end of the Middle Ages. It was demolished on the way to a new church, completed in 1692, and the [[Nurmij\u00e4rvi church|present church]], completed in 1793 and designed by master builder [[Matti \u00c5kerblom]], is the third in order.<ref name=\"tarmio\">Hannu Tarmio, Pentti Papunen & Kalevi Korpela: ''Suomenmaa 5: maantieteellis-yhteiskunnallinen tieto- ja hakuteos'', p. 405\u2013406. Porvoo-Helsinki: WSOY, 1973.</ref>\n\n[[Nurmij\u00e4rvi (lake)|Lake Nurmij\u00e4rvi]] has long been a strong farmer, and the share of fields in the total municipal area is almost one third, which is more than in many other municipalities in Finland. Horticultural crops have also been heavily cultivated and, for example, almost half of the [[Brassica oleracea|wild cabbage]] harvest in Finland is produced in Nurmij\u00e4rvi. Nevertheless, the municipality has not carried out further processing of agricultural products; for example, there has been no [[dairy]].<ref name=\"tarmio\"/>\n\nThe first industrial plants were born in the late 19th century, including Finland's first [[Pharmaceutical industry|pharmaceutical factory]] founded by [[pharmacist]] [[Albin Koponen (pharmacist)|Albin Koponen]] in Nurmij\u00e4rvi in 1899.<ref name=\"history\"/> The main products of the drug plant were filizine extracted from [[Dryopteris filix-mas|male fern]] root rhizomes, which were sold as ''[[Diphyllobothrium latum]]'' and [[cestoda]] medicines called Filisin and Filicon. The factory-produced filicin was sold encapsulated all the way to [[China]] and [[America]]. Today, trade, transport and other services account for two thirds, industry and construction for less than one third and agriculture for over 3% of the population. The largest individual employers are [[Altia|Altia Oyj]]<ref name=\"history\"/> and [[Teknos|Teknos Oy]] in Rajam\u00e4ki, [[Polimoon|Polimoon Oy]] in Klaukkala and [[Korsisaari|Korsisaari Oy]].\n\nIn the early 1960s, the settlement of Nurmij\u00e4rvi was evenly distributed in different parts of the municipality. However, [[Human migration|migration]] to Nurmij\u00e4rvi began to accelerate around the middle of the decade and the focus of settlement shifted to the southern parts of the municipality. Already in 1970 the majority (65%) of the inhabitants of Nurmij\u00e4rvi lived in [[urban settlement]]s. The largest [[Urban agglomeration|agglomeration]]s at that time were [[Klaukkala]] (3,500 inhabitants), [[Rajam\u00e4ki]] (3,400 inhabitants) and church village (2,800 inhabitants). Of these, the growth of Klaukkala and church village, in particular, has been based almost exclusively on the vicinity of the [[Greater Helsinki|Helsinki metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"history\"/><ref name=\"tarmio\"/> The most prominent farms on Lake Nurmij\u00e4rvi have been the manors of [[Numlahti Manor|Numlahti]] and [[Raala Manor|Raala]]. Before the departure of [[Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4]] in 1917, the [[Kyt\u00e4j\u00e4 Manor]] as well as the whole of the [[Kyt\u00e4j\u00e4]] village, were part of the Nurmij\u00e4rvi parish.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n== Politics ==\nResults<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nurmijarvenuutiset.fi/tulospalvelu#/kunnat/02_543|title=Tulospalvelu: Eduskuntavaalit 2019 - Nurmij\u00e4rvi|website=Nurmij\u00e4rven uutiset|accessdate=April 15, 2019}}</ref> of the [[2019 Finnish parliamentary election]] in Nurmij\u00e4rvi:\n\n*[[Finns Party]]   20.1%\n*[[National Coalition Party]]   19.4%\n*[[Social Democratic Party of Finland|Social Democratic Party]]   15.3%\n*[[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]]   14.6%\n*[[Green League]]   11.3%\n*[[Movement Now]]   5.9%\n*[[Left Alliance (Finland)|Left Alliance]]   4%\n*[[Blue Reform]]   3.2%\n*[[Christian Democrats (Finland)|Christian Democrats]]   2.7%\n*Other parties   3.5%\n\n== Friendship cities ==\n*{{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Lilla Edet Municipality|Lilla Edet]], Sweden\n*{{flagicon|Estonia}} [[Rapla Parish|Rapla]], Estonia\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.nurmijarvi.fi/en_GB/ Municipality of Nurmij\u00e4rvi] \u2013 Official site\n\n{{Uusimaa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nurmijarvi}}\n[[Category:Nurmij\u00e4rvi| ]]\n[[Category:Greater Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1605]]\n[[Category:1605 establishments in Sweden]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the former lake|Nurmij\u00e4rvi (lake)}}\n{{Infobox Finnish Municipality\n|name                   = Nurmij\u00e4rvi\n|official_name          = {{lang|fi|Nurmij\u00e4rven kunta}}<br />{{lang|sv|Nurmij\u00e4rvi kommun}}\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \n|native_name_lang       = \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Municipality\n|total_type             = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = Nurmij\u00e4rven kirkko.jpg\n|image_caption          = [[Nurmij\u00e4rvi church]]\n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              = \n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              = \n|image_shield           = Nurmijarvi.vaakuna.svg\n|shield_size            = \n|image_blank_emblem     = \n|blank_emblem_type      = \n|blank_emblem_size      = \n|image_map              = Nurmij\u00e4rvi.sijainti.suomi.2008.svg\n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = Location of Nurmij\u00e4rvi in [[Finland]]\n|image_dot_map          = \n|dot_mapsize            = \n|dot_map_caption        = \n|dot_x =  |dot_y = \n|pushpin_map            = <!-- name of a location map as per Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|province               = [[Southern Finland]]\n|region                 = [[Uusimaa]]\n|subregion              = Helsinki sub-region\n<!-- Smaller parts (e.g. boroughs of a city) and seat of government -->\n|seat_type              = \n|seat                   = \n|parts_type             = \n|parts_style            = <!-- =list (for list), coll (for collapsed list), para (for paragraph format)\n                               Default is list if up to 5 items, coll if more than 5-->\n|parts                  = <!-- parts text, or header for parts list -->\n|p1                     = \n|p2                     = <!-- etc. up to p10: for separate parts to be listed-->\n|government_footnotes   = \n|leader_title           = Municipal manager\n|leader_name            = Outi M\u00e4kel\u00e4\n|leader_title1          = \n|leader_name1           = \n|leader_title2          = \n|leader_name2           = \n|leader_title3          = \n|leader_name3           = \n|established_title      = [[Charter]]\n|established_date       = 1605\n|established_title2     = \n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     = \n|established_date3      = \n|extinct_title          = \n|extinct_date           = \n|area_urban_km2         = \n|area_metro_km2         = \n|population_metro       = \n|population_blank1_title  = \n|population_blank1        = \n|population_density_metro_km2 = \n|population_urban       = \n|population_density_urban_km2 = \n|population_note        = \n|finnish_official       = \n|swedish_official       = \n|sami_official          = \n|urbanisation           = \n|unemployment           = \n|blank1_name            = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank1_info            = [[Humid continental climate#Mild/cool summer subtype|Dfb]]\n|blank2_name            = \n|blank2_info            = \n|blank3_name            = \n|blank3_info            = \n|blank4_name            = \n|blank4_info            = \n|coordinates_type       = \n<!-- latNS=N and longEW=E set by default -->\n|coordinates            = {{coord|60|28|N|024|48.5|E|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = \n|postal_code            = \n|website                = [http://www.nurmijarvi.fi/ www.nurmijarvi.fi]\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Nurmij\u00e4rvi''' ({{IPA-fi|\u02c8nurmi\u02ccj\u00e6r\u028bi}}) is the most populated [[rural]] [[municipalities of Finland|municipality]] of [[Finland]], located {{convert|37|km}} north of the [[Capital (political)|capital]] [[Helsinki]]. The neighboring municipalities of Nurmij\u00e4rvi are [[Espoo]], [[Vantaa]], [[Tuusula]], [[Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4]] and [[Vihti]], and it is part of the [[Greater Helsinki]]. The population of the municipality is {{formatnum: {{Data Finland municipality/population count|{{PAGENAME}}}} }} inhabitants.<ref>[http://pxnet2.stat.fi/PXWeb/pxweb/fi/StatFin/StatFin__vrm__vamuu/statfin_vamuu_pxt_11lj.px/table/tableViewLayout1/ 11lj -- V\u00e4est\u00f6rakenteen ennakkotiedot alueittain, 2019M01*-2019M11*] (in Finnish)</ref>\n\nThe close proximity to Helsinki has led to a considerable growth of the major villages such as [[Klaukkala]], [[Rajam\u00e4ki]] and [[R\u00f6ykk\u00e4]]. Klaukkala is the biggest built-up area of Nurmij\u00e4rvi, which nowadays is considered a dormitory town of Helsinki. The church village (''Kirkonkyl\u00e4'') is the [[administrative centre]] of the municipality.\n\nNurmij\u00e4rvi literally means \"lawn lake\" although the [[Nurmij\u00e4rvi (lake)|lake that gave the municipality its name]] was drained in the early 20th century and is now nothing more than some flat fields near the village centre. Nurmij\u00e4rvi is one of three municipalities in the [[Uusimaa]] region that do not have a Swedish name; the others are [[Askola]] and [[M\u00e4nts\u00e4l\u00e4]].\n\nNurmij\u00e4rvi is best known as the birthplace of Finland's national author, [[Aleksis Kivi]]. The coat of arms of municipality refers to his most famous literal work, ''[[Seitsem\u00e4n veljest\u00e4]]'' (literally translated \"the seven brothers\") from 1870. On January 29, 2020, Nurmij\u00e4rvi declared itself officially the Capital of Aleksis Kivi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nurmijarvenuutiset.fi/artikkeli/837130-nurmijarvi-on-nyt-virallisesti-aleksis-kivi-paakaupunki|title=Nurmij\u00e4rvi on nyt virallisesti Aleksis Kivi p\u00e4\u00e4kaupunki|first=Riikka|last=Laine|publisher=Nurmij\u00e4rven Uutiset|date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020|language=fi}}</ref>\n\n[[Matti Vanhanen]], former [[Prime Minister of Finland]], lives in [[Leps\u00e4m\u00e4]] in Nurmij\u00e4rvi.\n\n== Geography ==\nNurmij\u00e4rvi is located in the central part of Uusimaa. [[Salpausselk\u00e4]] passes through the northern part of the municipality via R\u00f6ykk\u00e4, Kiljava and Rajam\u00e4ki, and the [[Vantaa (river)|River Vantaa]] flows through the Nukari and Palojoki rivers in the eastern part of the municipality. Nurmij\u00e4rvi's lowest terrain is in the Luhtajoki valley at Klaukkala and the highest in Salpausselk\u00e4 near Herunen.\n\nThere are few watercourses in the Nurmij\u00e4rvi area. The municipality is located along the middle course of the River Vantaa and there are two large [[rapids]], the Nukarinkoski and the Myllykoski. The River Vantaa is joined by the Palojoki River from Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4 and Tuusula, near the Palojoki village. The Leps\u00e4m\u00e4 River and the [[Luhtajoki|Luhtajoki River]] flowing in the southern part of the municipality join the Vantaa town side near the [[Keimola]] village before joining the River Vantaa. The largest lake in Nurmij\u00e4rvi is the Lake S\u00e4\u00e4ksi, which is partly situated on the northwest side of Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4, and the other lakes are Lake Vaaksi near R\u00f6ykk\u00e4 and Lake Valkj\u00e4rvi between Klaukkala and Perttula.\n\n=== Villages ===\n[[File:Centre_nurmij\u00e4rvi.jpg|thumb|Aleksis Kiven tie, one of the main streets of Nurmij\u00e4rvi's centre in January 2020.]]\n[[Herunen]], [[J\u00e4rventausta]], [[Kiljava]], [[Klaukkala]], [[Lepp\u00e4lampi]], [[Leps\u00e4m\u00e4]], [[Luhtajoki, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Luhtajoki]], [[Mets\u00e4kyl\u00e4, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Mets\u00e4kyl\u00e4]], [[Nukari]], [[Numlahti]], [[Nummenp\u00e4\u00e4]], [[Nurmij\u00e4rvi (village)|Nurmij\u00e4rvi]] (''Kirkonkyl\u00e4''), [[Palojoki]], [[Perttula]], [[Raala]], [[Rajam\u00e4ki]], [[R\u00f6ykk\u00e4]], [[Suomies]], [[Uotila, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Uotila]], [[Valkj\u00e4rvi, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Valkj\u00e4rvi]]\n\n== History ==\nThe area of what is now Nurmij\u00e4rvi was inhabited in prehistoric times, which refers to archaeological finds dating back to [[5th millennium BC|4500]]-[[4th millennium BC|3500 BC]]. At the time of the [[Middle Age]]s there was no permanent settlement in the area, but later the settlement spread from both [[Tavastia (historical province)|Tavastia]] and the coast to 15 villages in 1540 with 115 houses.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nurmijarvi.fi/kuntalaisen-palvelut/kulttuuri-ja-vapaa-aika/museo/nurmijarven-historiaa/nurmijarven-historiaa-lyhyesti/|title=Nurmij\u00e4rven historiaa lyhyesti|website=Nurmijarvi.fi|accessdate=February 22, 2020|language=fi}}</ref>\n\nAdministratively, Lake Nurmij\u00e4rvi has been formed by combining the districts of [[Loppi]], [[Vihti]] and [[Vantaa|Helsinki parish]]. The earliest documentary mention of Nurmij\u00e4rvi dates back to 1488, when the village of [[Uotila, Nurmij\u00e4rvi|Uotila]] was mentioned. According to the land register of 1539, Nurmij\u00e4rvi had 15 villages with a total of 113 houses. An independent congregation had already been formed in 1605 and the administrator of Nurmij\u00e4rvi was born in 1775, when the area had a population of 1471.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nThe first church in Lake Nurmij\u00e4rvi, which must have been St. Martin's Church in 1565, was built at the end of the Middle Ages. It was demolished on the way to a new church, completed in 1692, and the [[Nurmij\u00e4rvi church|present church]], completed in 1793 and designed by master builder [[Matti \u00c5kerblom]], is the third in order.<ref name=\"tarmio\">Hannu Tarmio, Pentti Papunen & Kalevi Korpela: ''Suomenmaa 5: maantieteellis-yhteiskunnallinen tieto- ja hakuteos'', p. 405\u2013406. Porvoo-Helsinki: WSOY, 1973.</ref>\n\n[[Nurmij\u00e4rvi (lake)|Lake Nurmij\u00e4rvi]] has long been a strong farmer, and the share of fields in the total municipal area is almost one third, which is more than in many other municipalities in Finland. Horticultural crops have also been heavily cultivated and, for example, almost half of the [[Brassica oleracea|wild cabbage]] harvest in Finland is produced in Nurmij\u00e4rvi. Nevertheless, the municipality has not carried out further processing of agricultural products; for example, there has been no [[dairy]].<ref name=\"tarmio\"/>\n\nThe first industrial plants were born in the late 19th century, including Finland's first [[Pharmaceutical industry|pharmaceutical factory]] founded by [[pharmacist]] [[Albin Koponen (pharmacist)|Albin Koponen]] in Nurmij\u00e4rvi in 1899.<ref name=\"history\"/> The main products of the drug plant were filizine extracted from [[Dryopteris filix-mas|male fern]] root rhizomes, which were sold as ''[[Diphyllobothrium latum]]'' and [[cestoda]] medicines called Filisin and Filicon. The factory-produced filicin was sold encapsulated all the way to [[China]] and [[America]]. Today, trade, transport and other services account for two thirds, industry and construction for less than one third and agriculture for over 3% of the population. The largest individual employers are [[Altia|Altia Oyj]]<ref name=\"history\"/> and [[Teknos|Teknos Oy]] in Rajam\u00e4ki, [[Polimoon|Polimoon Oy]] in Klaukkala and [[Korsisaari|Korsisaari Oy]].\n\nIn the early 1960s, the settlement of Nurmij\u00e4rvi was evenly distributed in different parts of the municipality. However, [[Human migration|migration]] to Nurmij\u00e4rvi began to accelerate around the middle of the decade and the focus of settlement shifted to the southern parts of the municipality. Already in 1970 the majority (65%) of the inhabitants of Nurmij\u00e4rvi lived in [[urban settlement]]s. The largest [[Urban agglomeration|agglomeration]]s at that time were [[Klaukkala]] (3,500 inhabitants), [[Rajam\u00e4ki]] (3,400 inhabitants) and church village (2,800 inhabitants). Of these, the growth of Klaukkala and church village, in particular, has been based almost exclusively on the vicinity of the [[Greater Helsinki|Helsinki metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"history\"/><ref name=\"tarmio\"/> The most prominent farms on Lake Nurmij\u00e4rvi have been the manors of [[Numlahti Manor|Numlahti]] and [[Raala Manor|Raala]]. Before the departure of [[Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4]] in 1917, the [[Kyt\u00e4j\u00e4 Manor]] as well as the whole of the [[Kyt\u00e4j\u00e4]] village, were part of the Nurmij\u00e4rvi parish.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n== Politics ==\nResults<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nurmijarvenuutiset.fi/tulospalvelu#/kunnat/02_543|title=Tulospalvelu: Eduskuntavaalit 2019 - Nurmij\u00e4rvi|website=Nurmij\u00e4rven uutiset|accessdate=April 15, 2019}}</ref> of the [[2019 Finnish parliamentary election]] in Nurmij\u00e4rvi:\n\n*[[Finns Party]]   20.1%\n*[[National Coalition Party]]   19.4%\n*[[Social Democratic Party of Finland|Social Democratic Party]]   15.3%\n*[[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]]   14.6%\n*[[Green League]]   11.3%\n*[[Movement Now]]   5.9%\n*[[Left Alliance (Finland)|Left Alliance]]   4%\n*[[Blue Reform]]   3.2%\n*[[Christian Democrats (Finland)|Christian Democrats]]   2.7%\n*Other parties   3.5%\n\n== Friendship cities ==\n*{{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Lilla Edet Municipality|Lilla Edet]], Sweden\n*{{flagicon|Estonia}} [[Rapla Parish|Rapla]], Estonia\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat-inline}}\n*[http://www.nurmijarvi.fi/en_GB/ Municipality of Nurmij\u00e4rvi] \u2013 Official site\n\n{{Uusimaa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nurmijarvi}}\n[[Category:Nurmij\u00e4rvi| ]]\n[[Category:Greater Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1605]]\n[[Category:1605 establishments in Sweden]]\n\n\n{{SouthernFinland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nurmij%C3%A4rvi"}
